# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: software-design
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] The **abstract factory pattern** in software engineering is a design pattern that provides a way to create families of related objects without imposing their concrete classes, by encapsulating a group of individual factories that have a common theme without specifying their concrete classes.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] According to this pattern, a client software component creates a concrete implementation of the abstract factory and then uses the generic interface of the factory to create the concrete objects that are part of the family.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] The client does not know which concrete objects it receives from each of these internal factories, as it uses only the generic interfaces of their products.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] This pattern separates the details of implementation of a set of objects from their general usage and relies on object composition, as object creation is implemented in methods exposed in the factory interface.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] Use of this pattern enables interchangeable concrete implementations without changing the code that uses them, even at runtime.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] However, employment of this pattern, as with similar design patterns, may result in unnecessary complexity and extra work in the initial writing of code.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] Additionally, higher levels of separation and abstraction can result in systems that are more difficult to debug and maintain.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] The abstract factory design pattern is one of the 23 patterns described in the 1994 *Design Patterns* book.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] Creating objects directly within the class that requires the objects is inflexible.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] Doing so commits the class to particular objects and makes it impossible to change the instantiation later without changing the class.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] It prevents the class from being reusable if other objects are required, and it makes the class difficult to test because real objects cannot be replaced with mock objects.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] A factory is the location of a concrete class in the code at which objects are constructed.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] Implementation of the pattern intends to insulate the creation of objects from their usage and to create families of related objects without depending on their concrete classes.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] This allows for new derived types to be introduced with no change to the code that uses the base class.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] This makes a class independent of how its objects are created.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] A class may be configured with a factory object, which it uses to create objects, and the factory object can be exchanged at runtime.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] The factory determines the concrete type of object to be created, and it is here that the object is actually created.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] However, the factory only returns a reference (in Java, for instance, by the **new** operator) or a pointer of an abstract type to the created concrete object.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] This insulates client code from object creation by having clients request that a factory object create an object of the desired abstract type and return an abstract pointer to the object.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] An example is an abstract factory class `DocumentCreator` that provides interfaces to create a number of products (e.g., `createLetter()` and `createResume()`).
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] Each of these products is derived from a simple abstract class such as`Letter` or `Resume` of which the client is aware.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] The client code would acquire an appropriate instance of the `DocumentCreator` and call its factory methods.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] Each of the resulting objects would be created from the same `DocumentCreator` implementation and would share a common theme.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] The client would only need to know how to handle the abstract `Letter` or `Resume` class, not the specific version that was created by the concrete factory.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] As the factory only returns a reference or a pointer to an abstract type, the client code that requested the object from the factory is not aware of—and is not burdened by—the actual concrete type of the object that was created.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] However, the abstract factory knows the type of a concrete object (and hence a concrete factory).
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] For instance, the factory may read the object's type from a configuration file.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] The client has no need to specify the type, as the type has already been specified in the configuration file.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] A sample UML class and sequence diagram for the abstract factory design pattern.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] In the above UML class diagram, the `Client` class that requires `ProductA` and `ProductB` objects does not instantiate the `ProductA1` and `ProductB1` classes directly.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] Instead, the `Client` refers to the `AbstractFactory` interface for creating objects, which makes the `Client` independent of how the objects are created (which concrete classes are instantiated).
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] The `Factory1` class implements the `AbstractFactory` interface by instantiating the `ProductA1` and `ProductB1` classes.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] The UML sequence diagram shows the runtime interactions.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] The `Client` object calls `createProductA()` on the `Factory1` object, which creates and returns a `ProductA1` object.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] Thereafter, the `Client` calls `createProductB()` on `Factory1`, which creates and returns a `ProductB1` object.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] The original structure of the abstract factory pattern, as defined in 1994 in *Design Patterns*, is based on abstract classes for the abstract factory and the abstract products to be created.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] The concrete factories and products are classes that specialize the abstract classes using inheritance.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] A more recent structure of the pattern is based on interfaces that define the abstract factory and the abstract products to be created.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] This design uses native support for interfaces or protocols in mainstream programming languages to avoid inheritance.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] In this case, the concrete factories and products are classes that realize the interface by implementing it.
[src:software-design/abstract-factory-pattern] This C++23 implementation is based on the pre-C++98 implementation in the book.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] In software engineering, the **adapter pattern** is a software design pattern (also known as wrapper, an alternative naming shared with the decorator pattern) that allows the interface of an existing class to be used as another interface.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] It is often used to make existing classes work with others without modifying their source code.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] An example is an adapter that converts the interface of a Document Object Model of an XML document into a tree structure that can be displayed.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] The adapter design pattern is one of the twenty-three well-known Gang of Four design patterns that describe how to solve recurring design problems to design flexible and reusable object-oriented software, that is, objects that are easier to implement, change, test, and reuse.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] Often an (already existing) class can not be reused only because its interface does not conform to the interface clients require.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] The key idea in this pattern is to work through a separate `adapter` that adapts the interface of an (already existing) class without changing it.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] Clients don't know whether they work with a `target` class directly or through an `adapter` with a class that does not have the `target` interface.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] An adapter allows two incompatible interfaces to work together.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] This is the real-world definition for an adapter.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] Interfaces may be incompatible, but the inner functionality should suit the need.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] The adapter design pattern allows otherwise incompatible classes to work together by converting the interface of one class into an interface expected by the clients.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] An adapter can be used when the wrapper must respect a particular interface and must support polymorphic behavior.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] Alternatively, a decorator pattern makes it possible to add or alter behavior of an interface at run-time, and a facade pattern is used when an easier or simpler interface to an underlying object is desired.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] In the above UML class diagram, the `client` class that requires a `target` interface cannot reuse the `adaptee` class directly because its interface doesn't conform to the `target` interface.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] In this adapter pattern, the adapter contains an instance of the class it wraps.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] In this situation, the adapter makes calls to the instance of the wrapped object.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] This adapter pattern uses multiple polymorphic interfaces implementing or inheriting both the interface that is expected and the interface that is pre-existing.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] It is typical for the expected interface to be created as a pure interface class, especially in languages such as Java (before JDK 1.8) that do not support multiple inheritance of classes.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] It is desired for `classA` to supply `classB` with some data, let us suppose some `String` data.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] However, suppose that the format of the string data must be varied.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] and perhaps create the correctly "formatting" object at runtime by means of the factory pattern.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] In this way, the use of adapters and providers allows multiple "views" by `ClassB` and `ClassC` into `ClassA` without having to alter the class hierarchy.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] In general, it permits a mechanism for arbitrary data flows between objects that can be retrofitted to an existing object hierarchy.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] When implementing the adapter pattern, for clarity, one can apply the class name `[ClassName]To[Interface]Adapter` to the provider implementation; for example, `DAOToProviderAdapter`.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] It should have a constructor method with an adaptee class variable as a parameter.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] This parameter will be passed to an instance member of `[ClassName]To[Interface]Adapter`.
[src:software-design/adapter-pattern] When the clientMethod is called, it will have access to the adaptee instance that allows for accessing the required data of the adaptee and performing operations on that data that generates the desired output.
[src:software-design/bridge-pattern] The **bridge pattern** is a design pattern used in software engineering that is meant to *"decouple an abstraction from its implementation so that the two can vary independently"*, introduced by the Gang of Four.
[src:software-design/bridge-pattern] The *bridge* uses encapsulation, aggregation, and can use inheritance to separate responsibilities into different classes.
[src:software-design/bridge-pattern] When a class varies often, the features of object-oriented programming become very useful because changes to a program's code can be made easily with minimal prior knowledge about the program.
[src:software-design/bridge-pattern] The bridge pattern is useful when both the class and what it does vary often.
[src:software-design/bridge-pattern] The class itself can be thought of as the *abstraction* and what the class can do as the *implementation*.
[src:software-design/bridge-pattern] The bridge pattern can also be thought of as two layers of abstraction.
[src:software-design/bridge-pattern] When there is only one fixed implementation, this pattern is known as the Pimpl idiom in the C++ world.
[src:software-design/bridge-pattern] The bridge pattern is often confused with the adapter pattern, and is often implemented using the object adapter pattern; e.g., in the Java code below.
[src:software-design/bridge-pattern] Variant: The implementation can be decoupled even more by deferring the presence of the implementation to the point where the abstraction is utilized.
[src:software-design/bridge-pattern] The Bridge design pattern is one of the twenty-three well-known *GoF design patterns* that describe how to solve recurring design problems to design flexible and reusable object-oriented software, that is, objects that are easier to implement, change, test, and reuse.
[src:software-design/bridge-pattern] What problems can the Bridge design pattern solve?
[src:software-design/bridge-pattern] When using subclassing, different subclasses implement an abstract class in different ways.
[src:software-design/bridge-pattern] But an implementation is bound to the abstraction at compile-time and cannot be changed at run-time.
[src:software-design/bridge-pattern] What solution does the Bridge design pattern describe?
[src:software-design/bridge-pattern] This enables to configure an `Abstraction` with an `Implementor` object at run-time.
[src:software-design/bridge-pattern] See also the Unified Modeling Language class and sequence diagram below.
[src:software-design/bridge-pattern] In the above Unified Modeling Language class diagram, an abstraction (`Abstraction`) is not implemented as usual in a single inheritance hierarchy.
[src:software-design/bridge-pattern] Instead, there is one hierarchy for an abstraction (`Abstraction`) and a separate hierarchy for its implementation (`Implementor`), which makes the two independent from each other.
[src:software-design/bridge-pattern] The `Abstraction` interface (`operation()`) is implemented in terms of (by delegating to) the `Implementor` interface (`imp.operationImp()`).
[src:software-design/bridge-pattern] The UML sequence diagram shows the run-time interactions: The `Abstraction1` object delegates implementation to the `Implementor1` object (by calling `operationImp()` on `Implementor1`), which performs the operation and returns to `Abstraction1`.
[src:software-design/bridge-pattern] Bridge pattern compose objects in tree structure.
[src:software-design/bridge-pattern] It decouples abstraction from implementation.
