[src:software-design/builder-pattern] The **builder pattern** is a design pattern that provides a flexible solution to various object creation problems in object-oriented programming.
[src:software-design/builder-pattern] The builder pattern separates the construction of a complex object from its representation.
[src:software-design/builder-pattern] It is one of the 23 classic design patterns described in the book *Design Patterns* and is sub-categorized as a creational pattern.
[src:software-design/builder-pattern] Creating and assembling the parts of a complex object directly within a class is inflexible.
[src:software-design/builder-pattern] It commits the class to creating a particular representation of the complex object and makes it impossible to change the representation later independently from (without having to change) the class.
[src:software-design/builder-pattern] A class (the same construction process) can delegate to different `Builder` objects to create different representations of a complex object.
[src:software-design/builder-pattern] The intent of the builder design pattern is to separate the construction of a complex object from its representation.
[src:software-design/builder-pattern] By doing so, the same construction process can create different representations.
[src:software-design/builder-pattern] In the above UML class diagram, the `Director` class doesn't create and assemble the `ProductA1` and `ProductB1` objects directly.
[src:software-design/builder-pattern] Instead, the `Director` refers to the `Builder` interface for building (creating and assembling) the parts of a complex object, which makes the `Director` independent of which concrete classes are instantiated (which representation is created).
[src:software-design/builder-pattern] The `Builder1` class implements the `Builder` interface by creating and assembling the `ProductA1` and `ProductB1` objects.
[src:software-design/builder-pattern] The UML sequence diagram shows the run-time interactions: The `Director` object calls `buildPartA()` on the `Builder1` object, which creates and assembles the `ProductA1` object.
[src:software-design/builder-pattern] Thereafter, the `Director` calls `buildPartB()` on `Builder1`, which creates and assembles the `ProductB1` object.
[src:software-design/builder-pattern] Abstract interface for creating objects (product).
[src:software-design/builder-pattern] Constructs and assembles parts to build the objects.
[src:software-design/builder-pattern] The Director assembles a bicycle instance in the example above, delegating the construction to a separate builder object that has been given to the Director by the Client.
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] In object-oriented design, the **chain-of-responsibility pattern** is a behavioral design pattern consisting of a source of command objects and a series of **processing objects**.
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] Each processing object contains logic that defines the types of command objects that it can handle; the rest are passed to the next processing object in the chain.
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] A mechanism also exists for adding new processing objects to the end of this chain.
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] In a variation of the standard chain-of-responsibility model, some handlers may act as dispatchers, capable of sending commands out in a variety of directions, forming a *tree of responsibility*.
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] In some cases, this can occur recursively, with processing objects calling higher-up processing objects with commands that attempt to solve some smaller part of the problem; in this case recursion continues until the command is processed, or the entire tree has been explored.
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] An XML interpreter might work in this manner.
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] This pattern promotes the idea of loose coupling.
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] The chain-of-responsibility pattern is structurally nearly identical to the decorator pattern, the difference being that for the decorator, all classes handle the request, while for the chain of responsibility, exactly one of the classes in the chain handles the request.
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] This is a strict definition of the Responsibility concept in the *Gang of Four Design Patterns* book.
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] However, many implementations (such as loggers below, or UI event handling, or servlet filters in Java, etc.) allow several elements in the chain to take responsibility.
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] Implementing a request directly within the class that sends the request is inflexible because it couples the class to a particular receiver and makes it impossible to support multiple receivers.
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] This enables us to send a request to a chain of receivers without having to know which one handles the request.
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] The request gets passed along the chain until a receiver handles the request.
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] The sender of a request is no longer coupled to a particular receiver.
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] See also the UML class and sequence diagram below.
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] In the above UML class diagram, the `Sender` class doesn't refer to a particular receiver class directly.
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] Instead, `Sender` refers to the `Handler` interface for handling a request (`handler.handleRequest()`), which makes the `Sender` independent of which receiver handles the request.
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] The `Receiver1`, `Receiver2`, and `Receiver3` classes implement the `Handler` interface by either handling or forwarding a request (depending on run-time conditions).
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] The UML sequence diagram shows the run-time interactions: In this example, the `Sender` object calls `handleRequest()` on the `receiver1` object (of type `Handler`).
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] The `receiver1` forwards the request to `receiver2`, which in turn forwards the request to `receiver3`, which handles (performs) the request.
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] This C++23 implementation is based on the pre C++98 implementation in the book.
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] The Cocoa and Cocoa Touch frameworks, used for OS X and iOS applications respectively, actively use the chain-of-responsibility pattern for handling events.
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] Objects that participate in the chain are called *responder* objects, inheriting from the `NSResponder` (OS X)/`UIResponder` (iOS) class.
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] All view objects (`NSView`/`UIView`), view controller objects (`NSViewController`/`UIViewController`), window objects (`NSWindow`/`UIWindow`), and the application object (`NSApplication`/`UIApplication`) are responder objects.
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] Typically, when a view receives an event which it can't handle, it dispatches it to its superview until it reaches the view controller or window object.
[src:software-design/chain-of-responsibility-pattern] If the window can't handle the event, the event is dispatched to the application object, which is the last object in the chain.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] In object-oriented programming, the **command pattern** is a behavioral design pattern in which an object is used to encapsulate all information needed to perform an action or trigger an event at a later time.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] This information includes the method name, the object that owns the method and values for the method parameters.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] Four terms always associated with the command pattern are *command*, *receiver*, *invoker* and *client*.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] A *command* object knows about *receiver* and invokes a method of the receiver.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] Values for parameters of the receiver method are stored in the command.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] The receiver object to execute these methods is also stored in the command object by aggregation.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] The *receiver* then does the work when the `execute()` method in *command* is called.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] An *invoker* object knows how to execute a command, and optionally does bookkeeping about the command execution.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] The invoker does not know anything about a concrete command, it knows only about the command *interface*.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] Invoker object(s), command objects and receiver objects are held by a *client* object.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] The *client* decides which receiver objects it assigns to the command objects, and which commands it assigns to the invoker.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] The client decides which commands to execute at which points.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] To execute a command, it passes the command object to the invoker object.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] Using command objects makes it easier to construct general components that need to delegate, sequence or execute method calls at a time of their choosing without the need to know the class of the method or the method parameters.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] Using an invoker object allows bookkeeping about command executions to be conveniently performed, as well as implementing different modes for commands, which are managed by the invoker object, without the need for the client to be aware of the existence of bookkeeping or modes.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] The central ideas of this design pattern closely mirror the semantics of first-class functions and higher-order functions in functional programming languages.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] Specifically, the invoker object is a higher-order function of which the command object is a first-class argument.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] The command design pattern is one of the twenty-three well-known *GoF design patterns* that describe how to solve recurring design problems to design flexible and reusable object-oriented software, that is, objects that are easier to implement, change, test, and reuse.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] Implementing (hard-wiring) a request directly into a class is inflexible because it couples the class to a particular request at compile-time, which makes it impossible to specify a request at run-time.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] This enables one to configure a class with a command object that is used to perform a request.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] The class is no longer coupled to a particular request and has no knowledge (is independent) of how the request is carried out.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] In the above UML class diagram, the `Invoker` class doesn't implement a request directly.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] Instead, `Invoker` refers to the `Command` interface to perform a request (`command.execute()`), which makes the `Invoker` independent of how the request is performed.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] The `Command1` class implements the `Command` interface by performing an action on a receiver (`receiver1.action1()`).
[src:software-design/command-pattern] The UML sequence diagram shows the run-time interactions: The `Invoker` object calls `execute()` on a `Command1` object.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] `Command1` calls `action1()` on a `Receiver1` object, which performs the request.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] If all user actions are represented by command objects, a program can record a sequence of actions simply by keeping a list of the command objects as they are executed.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] It can then "play back" the same actions by executing the same command objects again in sequence.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] method, and user actions can then be easily recorded as scripts.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] Using languages such as Java where code can be streamed/slurped from one location to another via URLClassloaders and Codebases the commands can enable new behavior to be delivered to remote locations (EJB Command, Master Worker).
[src:software-design/command-pattern] If all user actions in a program are implemented as command objects, the program can keep a stack of the most recently executed commands.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] It is possible to send whole command objects across the network to be executed on the other machines, for example player actions in computer games.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] Suppose a program has a sequence of commands that it executes in order.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] method, the program can easily estimate the total duration.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] It can show a progress bar that meaningfully reflects how close the program is to completing all the tasks.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] method that adds a work item to an internal queue of tasks waiting to be done.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] It maintains a pool of threads that execute commands from the queue.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] The items in the queue are command objects.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] that allows the thread pool to execute the command even though the thread pool class itself was written without any knowledge of the specific tasks for which it would be used.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] or software installer may keep a list of operations that have been or will be performed.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] For example, if two database tables that refer to each other must be updated, and the second update fails, the transaction can be rolled back, so that the first table does not now contain an invalid reference.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] Often a wizard presents several pages of configuration for a single action that happens only when the user clicks the "Finish" button on the last page.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] In these cases, a natural way to separate user interface code from application code is to implement the wizard using a command object.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] The command object is created when the wizard is first displayed.
[src:software-design/command-pattern] Each wizard page stores its GUI changes in the command object, so the object is populated as the user progresses.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] In software engineering, the **composite pattern** is a partitioning design pattern.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] The composite pattern describes a group of objects that are treated the same way as a single instance of the same type of object.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] The intent of a composite is to "compose" objects into tree structures to represent part-whole hierarchies.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] Implementing the composite pattern lets clients treat individual objects and compositions uniformly.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] The Composite design pattern is one of the twenty-three well-known *GoF design patterns* that describe how to solve recurring design problems to design flexible and reusable object-oriented software, that is, objects that are easier to implement, change, test, and reuse.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] When defining (1) `Part` objects and (2) `Whole` objects that act as containers for `Part` objects, clients must treat them separately, which complicates client code.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] This enables clients to work through the `Component` interface to treat `Leaf` and `Composite` objects uniformly: `Leaf` objects perform a request directly, and `Composite` objects forward the request to their child components recursively downwards the tree structure.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] This makes client classes easier to implement, change, test, and reuse.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] See also the UML class and object diagram below.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] When dealing with Tree-structured data, programmers often have to discriminate between a leaf-node and a branch.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] This makes code more complex, and therefore, more error prone.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] The solution is an interface that allows treating complex and primitive objects uniformly.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] In object-oriented programming, a composite is an object designed as a composition of one-or-more similar objects, all exhibiting similar functionality.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] This is known as a "has-a" relationship between objects.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] The key concept is that you can manipulate a single instance of the object just as you would manipulate a group of them.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] The operations you can perform on all the composite objects often have a least common denominator relationship.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] For example, if defining a system to portray grouped shapes on a screen, it would be useful to define resizing a group of shapes to have the same effect (in some sense) as resizing a single shape.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] Composite should be used when clients ignore the difference between compositions of objects and individual objects.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] If programmers find that they are using multiple objects in the same way, and often have nearly identical code to handle each of them, then composite is a good choice; it is less complex in this situation to treat primitives and composites as homogeneous.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] In the above UML class diagram, the `Client` class doesn't refer to the `Leaf` and `Composite` classes directly (separately).
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] Instead, the `Client` refers to the common `Component` interface and can treat `Leaf` and `Composite` uniformly.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] The `Leaf` class has no children and implements the `Component` interface directly.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] The `Composite` class maintains a container of child `Component` objects (`children`) and forwards requests to these `children` (`for each child in children: child.operation()`).
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] The object collaboration diagram shows the run-time interactions: In this example, the `Client` object sends a request to the top-level `Composite` object (of type `Component`) in the tree structure.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] The request is forwarded to (performed on) all child `Component` objects (`Leaf` and `Composite` objects) downwards the tree structure.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] The GoF authors present a variant of the Composite design pattern that emphasizes *transparency* over *type safety* and discuss the tradeoffs of the two approaches.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] The type-safe approach is particularly palatable if the composite structure is fixed post construction: the construction code does not require transparency because it needs to know the types involved in order to construct the composite.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] If downstream, the code does not need to modify the structure, then the child manipulation operations do not need to be present on the `Component` interface.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] As it is described in Design Patterns, the pattern also involves including the child-manipulation methods in the main Component interface, not just the Composite subclass.
[src:software-design/composite-pattern] More recent descriptions sometimes omit these methods.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] In object-oriented programming, the **decorator pattern** is a design pattern that allows behavior to be added to an individual object dynamically, without affecting the behavior of other instances of the same class.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] The decorator pattern is often useful for adhering to the Single Responsibility Principle, as it enables functionality to be distributed across classes with distinct concerns.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] It also supports the Open–Closed Principle, since a class's functionality can be extended without modifying its source code.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Using decorators can be more flexible and efficient than subclassing, as an object's behavior can be augmented or combined at runtime without creating an entirely new class hierarchy.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] The *decorator* design pattern is one of the twenty-three *Gang-of-Four design patterns*; these describe how to solve recurring design problems and design flexible and reusable object-oriented software—that is, objects which are easier to implement, change, test, and reuse.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] The decorator pattern provides a flexible alternative to subclassing for extending functionality.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] When using subclassing, different subclasses extend a class in different ways.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] However, an extension is bound to the class at compile-time and can't be changed at run-time.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] The decorator pattern allows responsibilities to be added (and removed from) an object dynamically at run-time.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] This allows working with different `Decorator` objects to extend the functionality of an object dynamically at run-time.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] The decorator pattern can be used to extend (decorate) the functionality of a certain object statically, or in some cases at run-time, independently of other instances of the same class, provided some groundwork is done at design time.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] This is achieved by designing a new *Decorator* class that wraps the original class.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] In the ConcreteDecorator class, override any *Component* method(s) whose behavior needs to be modified.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] This pattern is designed so that multiple decorators can be stacked on top of each other, each time adding a new functionality to the overridden method(s).
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Note that decorators and the original class object share a common set of features.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] In the previous diagram, the operation() method was available in both the decorated and undecorated versions.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] The decoration features (e.g., methods, properties, or other members) are usually defined by an interface, mixin (a.k.a. trait) or class inheritance which is shared by the decorators and the decorated object.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] In the previous example, the class *Component* is inherited by both the ConcreteComponent and the subclasses that descend from *Decorator*.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] The decorator pattern is an alternative to subclassing.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Subclassing introduces additional behavior by deriving new classes at compile time, and such modifications affect all instances of the original class.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] In contrast, the Decorator pattern allows new behaviors to be dynamically added to selected objects at run-time without impacting other instances of the same class.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] This design enables more fine-grained and flexible behavior extension, thereby improving code reusability and maintainability.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] This difference becomes most important when there are several *independent* ways of extending functionality.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] In some object-oriented programming languages, classes cannot be created at runtime, and it is typically not possible to predict, at design time, what combinations of extensions will be needed.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] This would mean that a new class would have to be made for every possible combination.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] By contrast, decorators are objects, created at runtime, and can be combined on a per-use basis.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] The I/O Streams implementations of both Java and the .NET Framework incorporate the decorator pattern.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] As an example, consider a window in a windowing system.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] To allow scrolling of the window's contents, one may wish to add horizontal or vertical scrollbars to it, as appropriate.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Assume windows are represented by instances of the *Window* interface, and assume this class has no functionality for adding scrollbars.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] One could create a subclass *ScrollingWindow* that provides them, or create a *ScrollingWindowDecorator* that adds this functionality to existing *Window* objects.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] At this point, either solution would be fine.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Now, assume one also desires the ability to add borders to windows.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Again, the original *Window* class has no support.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] The *ScrollingWindow* subclass now poses a problem, because it has effectively created a new kind of window.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] If one wishes to add border support to many but not *all* windows, one must create subclasses *WindowWithBorder* and *ScrollingWindowWithBorder*, etc.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] This problem gets worse with every new feature or window subtype to be added.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] For the decorator solution, a new *BorderedWindowDecorator* is created.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Any combination of *ScrollingWindowDecorator* or *BorderedWindowDecorator* can decorate existing windows.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] If the functionality needs to be added to all Windows, the base class can be modified.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] On the other hand, sometimes (e.g., using external frameworks) it is not possible, legal, or convenient to modify the base class.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] In the previous example, the *SimpleWindow* and *WindowDecorator* classes implement the *Window* interface, which defines the *draw()* method and the *getDescription()* method that are required in this scenario, in order to decorate a window control.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Adding or removing decorators on command (like a button press) is a common UI pattern, often implemented along with the Command design pattern.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] For example, a text editing application might have a button to highlight text.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] On button press, the individual text glyphs currently selected will all be wrapped in decorators that modify their draw() function, causing them to be drawn in a highlighted manner (a real implementation would probably also use a demarcation system to maximize efficiency).
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Applying or removing decorators based on changes in state is another common use case.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Depending on the scope of the state, decorators can be applied or removed in bulk.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Similarly, the State design pattern can be implemented using decorators instead of subclassed objects encapsulating the changing functionality.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] The use of decorators in this manner makes the State object's internal state and functionality more compositional and capable of handling arbitrary complexity.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Decoration is also often used in the Flyweight design pattern.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Flyweight objects are divided into two components: an invariant component that is shared between all flyweight objects; and a variant, decorated component that may be partially shared or completely unshared.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] This partitioning of the flyweight object is intended to reduce memory consumption.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] The decorators are typically cached and reused as well.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] The decorators will all contain a common reference to the shared, invariant object.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Applying combinations of decorators in diverse ways to a collection of objects introduces some problems interfacing with the collection in a way that takes full advantage of the functionality added by the decorators.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] The use of an Adapter or Visitor patterns can be useful in such cases.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Adapter patterns can unify disparate interfaces into a common, expected API.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Similarly, the Visitor pattern enables operations to be performed across a structure of decorated objects without embedding the operation logic within the objects themselves.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Interfacing with multiple layers of decorators poses additional challenges and logic of Adapters and Visitors must be designed to account for that.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Decorators support a compositional rather than a top-down, hierarchical approach to extending functionality.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] A decorator makes it possible to add or alter behavior of an interface at run-time.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] They can be used to wrap objects in a multilayered, arbitrary combination of ways.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Doing the same with subclasses means implementing complex networks of multiple inheritance, which is memory-inefficient and at a certain point just cannot scale.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Likewise, attempting to implement the same functionality with properties bloats each instance of the object with unnecessary properties.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] For the above reasons decorators are often considered a memory-efficient alternative to subclassing.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Decorators can also be used to specialize objects which are not subclassable, whose characteristics need to be altered at runtime (as mentioned elsewhere), or generally objects that are lacking in some needed functionality.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] The decorator pattern also can augment the Facade pattern.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] A facade is designed to simply interface with the complex system it encapsulates, but it does not add functionality to the system.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] However, the wrapping of a complex system provides a space that may be used to introduce new functionality based on the coordination of subcomponents in the system.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] For example, a facade pattern may unify many different languages dictionaries under one multi-language dictionary interface.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] The new interface may also provide new functions for translating words between languages.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] This is a hybrid pattern - the unified interface provides a space for augmentation.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Think of decorators as not being limited to wrapping individual objects, but capable of wrapping clusters of objects in this hybrid approach as well.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] As an alternative to the decorator pattern, the adapter can be used when the wrapper must respect a particular interface and must support polymorphic behavior, and the Facade when an easier or simpler interface to an underlying object is desired.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] In the above UML class diagram, the abstract `Decorator` class maintains a reference (`component`) to the decorated object (`Component`) and forwards all requests to it (`component.operation()`).
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] This makes `Decorator` transparent (invisible) to clients of `Component`.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Subclasses (`Decorator1`,`Decorator2`) implement additional behavior (`addBehavior()`) that should be added to the `Component` (before/after forwarding a request to it).
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] The sequence diagram shows the run-time interactions: The `Client` object works through `Decorator1` and `Decorator2` objects to extend the functionality of a `Component1` object.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] The `Client` calls `operation()` on `Decorator1`, which forwards the request to `Decorator2`.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] `Decorator2` performs `addBehavior()` after forwarding the request to `Component1` and returns to `Decorator1`, which performs `addBehavior()` and returns to the `Client`.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] This implementation (which uses C++23 features) is based on the pre C++98 implementation in the book.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Full example can be tested on a godbolt page.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] Two options are presented here: first, a dynamic, runtime-composable decorator (has issues with calling decorated functions unless proxied explicitly) and a decorator that uses mixin inheritance.
[src:software-design/decorator-pattern] This example demonstrates a static Decorator implementation, which is possible due to C++ ability to inherit from the template argument.
