[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Under domain-driven design, the structure and language of software code (class names, class methods, class variables) should match the business domain.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] For example: if software processes loan applications, it might have classes like "loan application", "customers", and methods such as "accept offer" and "withdraw".
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Critics of domain-driven design argue that developers must typically implement a great deal of isolation and encapsulation to maintain the model as a pure and helpful construct.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] While domain-driven design provides benefits such as maintainability, Microsoft recommends it only for complex domains where the model provides clear benefits in formulating a common understanding of the domain.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] The term was coined by Eric Evans in his book of the same name published in 2003.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Domain-driven design articulates a number of high-level concepts and practices.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Of primary importance is a *domain* of the software, the subject area to which the user applies a program.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Software's developers build a *domain model*: a system of abstractions that describes selected aspects of a domain and can be used to solve problems related to that domain.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] These aspects of domain-driven design aim to foster a *common language* shared by domain experts, users, and developers—the *ubiquitous language*.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] The ubiquitous language is used in the domain model and for describing system requirements.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Ubiquitous language is one of the pillars of DDD together with *strategic design* and *tactical design*.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] In domain-driven design, the domain layer is one of the common layers in an object-oriented multilayered architecture.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Domain-driven design recognizes multiple kinds of models.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] For example, an *entity* is an object defined not by its attributes, but its identity.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] As an example, most airlines assign a unique number to seats on every flight: this is the seat's identity.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] In contrast, a *value object* is an immutable object that contains attributes but has no conceptual identity.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] When people exchange business cards, for instance, they only care about the information on the card (its attributes) rather than trying to distinguish between each unique card.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Models can also define *events* (something that happened in the past).
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] A domain event is an event that domain experts care about.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Models can be bound together by a root entity to become an *aggregate*.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Objects outside the aggregate are allowed to hold references to the root but not to any other object of the aggregate.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] The aggregate root checks the consistency of changes in the aggregate.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Drivers do not have to individually control each wheel of a car, for instance: they simply drive the car.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] In this context, a car is an aggregate of several other objects (the engine, the brakes, the headlights, etc.).
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] In domain-driven design, an object's creation is often separated from the object itself.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] A *repository*, for instance, is an object with methods for retrieving domain objects from a data store (e.g. a database).
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Similarly, a factory is an object with methods for directly creating domain objects.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] When part of a program's functionality does not conceptually belong to any object, it is typically expressed as a service.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] There are different types of events in DDD, and opinions on their classification may vary.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Domain events signify important occurrences within a specific business domain.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] These events are restricted to a bounded context and are vital for preserving business logic.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Typically, domain events have lighter payloads, containing only the necessary information for processing.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] This is because event listeners are generally within the same service, where their requirements are more clearly understood.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] On the other hand, integration events serve to communicate changes across different bounded contexts.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] They are crucial for ensuring data consistency throughout the entire system.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Integration events tend to have more complex payloads with additional attributes, as the needs of potential listeners can differ significantly.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] This often leads to a more thorough approach to communication, resulting in overcommunication to ensure that all relevant information is effectively shared.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Context Mapping identifies and defines the boundaries of different domains or subdomains within a larger system.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] It helps visualize how these contexts interact and relate to each other.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Although domain-driven design is not inherently tied to object-oriented approaches, in practice, it exploits the advantages of such techniques.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] These include entities/aggregate roots as receivers of commands/method invocations, the encapsulation of state within foremost aggregate roots, and on a higher architectural level, bounded contexts.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] As a result, domain-driven design is often associated with Plain Old Java Objects and Plain Old CLR Objects, which are technical implementation details, specific to Java and the .NET Framework respectively.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] These terms reflect a growing view that domain objects should be defined purely by the business behavior of the domain, rather than by a more specific technology framework.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Similarly, the naked objects pattern holds that the user interface can simply be a reflection of a good enough domain model.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Requiring the user interface to be a direct reflection of the domain model will force the design of a better domain model.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Domain-driven design has influenced other approaches to software development.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Domain-specific modeling, for instance, is domain-driven design applied with domain-specific languages.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Domain-driven design does not specifically require the use of a domain-specific language, though it could be used to help define a domain-specific language and support domain-specific multimodeling.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] In turn, aspect-oriented programming makes it easy to factor out technical concerns (such as security, transaction management, logging) from a domain model, letting them focus purely on the business logic.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] While domain-driven design is compatible with model-driven engineering and model-driven architecture, the intent behind the two concepts is different.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Model-driven architecture is more concerned with translating a model into code for different technology platforms than defining better domain models.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] However, the techniques provided by model-driven engineering (to model domains, to create domain-specific languages to facilitate the communication between domain experts and developers,...) facilitate domain-driven design in practice and help practitioners get more out of their models.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Thanks to model-driven engineering's model transformation and code generation techniques, the domain model can be used to generate the actual software system that will manage it.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Command Query Responsibility Segregation (CQRS) is an architectural pattern for separating reading data (a 'query') from writing to data (a 'command').
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] CQRS derives from Command and Query Separation (CQS), coined by Bertrand Meyer.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Commands mutate state and are approximately equivalent to method invocation on aggregate roots or entities.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Queries read state but do not mutate it.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] While CQRS does not require domain-driven design, it makes the distinction between commands and queries explicit with the concept of an aggregate root.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] The idea is that a given aggregate root has a method that corresponds to a command and a command handler invokes the method on the aggregate root.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] The aggregate root is responsible for performing the logic of the operation and either yielding a failure response or just mutating its own state that can be written to a data store.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] The command handler pulls in infrastructure concerns related to saving the aggregate root's state and creating needed contexts (e.g., transactions).
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Event storming is a collaborative, workshop-based modeling technique which can be used as a precursor in the context of Domain-Driven Design (DDD) to identify and understand domain events.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] This interactive discovery process involves stakeholders, domain experts, and developers working together to visualize the flow of domain events, their causes, and their effects, fostering a shared understanding of the domain.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] The technique often uses color-coded sticky notes to represent different elements, such as domain events, aggregates, and external systems, facilitating a clear and structured exploration of the domain.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Event storming can aid in discovering subdomains, bounded contexts, and aggregate boundaries, which are key constructs in DDD.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] By focusing on 'what happens' in the domain, the technique can help uncover business processes, dependencies, and interactions, providing a foundation for implementing DDD principles and aligning system design with business goals.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Event sourcing is an architectural pattern in which entities track their internal state not by means of direct serialization or object-relational mapping, but by reading and committing events to an event store.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] When event sourcing is combined with CQRS and domain-driven design, aggregate roots are responsible for validating and applying commands (often by having their instance methods invoked from a Command Handler), and then publishing events.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] This is also the foundation upon which the aggregate roots base their logic for dealing with method invocations.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Hence, the input is a command and the output is one or many events which are saved to an event store, and then often published on a message broker for those interested (such as an application's view).
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Modeling aggregate roots to output events can isolate internal state even further than when projecting read-data from entities, as in standard *n*-tier data-passing architectures.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] One significant benefit is that axiomatic theorem provers (e.g.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Microsoft Contracts and CHESS) are easier to apply, as the aggregate root comprehensively hides its internal state.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] Events are often persisted based on the version of the aggregate root instance, which yields a domain model that synchronizes in distributed systems through optimistic concurrency.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] A bounded context, a fundamental concept in Domain-Driven Design (DDD), defines a specific area within which a domain model is consistent and valid, ensuring clarity and separation of concerns.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] In microservices architecture, a bounded context often maps to a microservice, but this relationship can vary depending on the design approach.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] A one-to-one relationship, where each bounded context is implemented as a single microservice, is typically ideal as it maintains clear boundaries, reduces coupling, and enables independent deployment and scaling.
[src:software-design/domain-driven-design] The choice of relationship should balance the principles of DDD with the system's business goals, technical constraints, and operational requirements.
[src:software-design/facade-pattern] The **facade pattern** (also spelled *façade*) is a software design pattern commonly used in object-oriented programming.
[src:software-design/facade-pattern] Analogous to a façade in architecture, it is an object that serves as a front-facing interface masking more complex underlying or structural code.
[src:software-design/facade-pattern] Developers often use the facade design pattern when a system is very complex or difficult to understand because the system has many interdependent classes or because its source code is unavailable.
[src:software-design/facade-pattern] This pattern hides the complexities of the larger system and provides a simpler interface to the client.
[src:software-design/facade-pattern] It typically involves a single wrapper class that contains a set of members required by the client.
[src:software-design/facade-pattern] These members access the system on behalf of the facade client and hide the implementation details.
[src:software-design/facade-pattern] The Facade design pattern is one of the twenty-three well-known *GoF design patterns* that describe how to solve recurring design problems to design flexible and reusable object-oriented software, that is, objects that are easier to implement, change, test, and reuse.
[src:software-design/facade-pattern] What problems can the Facade design pattern solve?
[src:software-design/facade-pattern] Clients that access a complex subsystem directly refer to (depend on) many different objects having different interfaces (tight coupling), which makes the clients hard to implement, change, test, and reuse.
[src:software-design/facade-pattern] What solution does the Facade design pattern describe?
[src:software-design/facade-pattern] This enables to work through a `Facade` object to minimize the dependencies on a subsystem.
[src:software-design/facade-pattern] A Facade is used when an easier or simpler interface to an underlying object is desired.
[src:software-design/facade-pattern] Alternatively, an adapter can be used when the wrapper must respect a particular interface and must support polymorphic behavior.
[src:software-design/facade-pattern] A good example of where a facade is used is in register indexed values like Modbus, I2C or Special function register.
[src:software-design/facade-pattern] In this UML class diagram, the `Client` class doesn't access the subsystem classes directly.
[src:software-design/facade-pattern] Instead, the `Client` works through a `Facade` class that implements a simple interface in terms of (by delegating to) the subsystem classes (`Class1`, `Class2`, and `Class3`).
[src:software-design/facade-pattern] The `Client` depends only on the simple `Facade` interface and is independent of the complex subsystem.
[src:software-design/facade-pattern] The sequence diagram shows the run-time interactions: The `Client` object works through a `Facade` object that delegates the request to the `Class1`, `Class2`, and `Class3` instances that perform the request.
[src:software-design/facade-pattern] The facade class abstracts Packages 1, 2, and 3 from the rest of the application.
[src:software-design/facade-pattern] The objects are using the facade pattern to access resources from the packages.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] In object-oriented programming, the **factory method pattern** is a design pattern that uses factory methods to deal with the problem of creating objects without having to specify their exact classes.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] Rather than by calling a constructor, this is accomplished by invoking a factory method to create an object.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] Factory methods can be specified in an interface and implemented by subclasses or implemented in a base class and optionally overridden by subclasses.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] It is one of the 23 classic design patterns described in the book *Design Patterns* and is subcategorized as a creational pattern.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] This enables the creation of subclasses that can change the way in which an object is created (for example, by redefining which class to instantiate).
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] According to *Design Patterns: Elements of Reusable Object-Oriented Software*: "Define an interface for creating an object, but let subclasses decide which class to instantiate.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] Creating an object often requires complex processes not appropriate to include within a composing object.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] The object's creation may lead to a significant duplication of code, may require information inaccessible to the composing object, may not provide a sufficient level of abstraction or may otherwise not be included in the composing object's concerns.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] The factory method design pattern handles these problems by defining a separate method for creating the objects, which subclasses can then override to specify the derived type of product that will be created.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] The factory method pattern relies on inheritance, as object creation is delegated to subclasses that implement the factory method to create objects.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] The pattern can also rely on the implementation of an interface.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] In the above UML class diagram, the `Creator` class that requires a `Product` object does not instantiate the `Product1` class directly.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] Instead, the `Creator` refers to a separate `factoryMethod()` to create a product object, which makes the `Creator` independent of the exact concrete class that is instantiated.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] Subclasses of `Creator` can redefine which class to instantiate.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] In this example, the `Creator1` subclass implements the abstract `factoryMethod()` by instantiating the `Product1` class.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] A maze game may be played in two modes, one with regular rooms that are only connected with adjacent rooms, and one with magic rooms that allow players to be transported at random.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] `Room` is the base class for a final product (`MagicRoom` or `OrdinaryRoom`).
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] `MazeGame` declares the abstract factory method to produce such a base product.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] `MagicRoom` and `OrdinaryRoom` are subclasses of the base product implementing the final product.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] `MagicMazeGame` and `OrdinaryMazeGame` are subclasses of `MazeGame` implementing the factory method producing the final products.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] Factory methods thus decouple callers (`MazeGame`) from the implementation of the concrete classes.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] This makes the `new` operator redundant, allows adherence to the open–closed principle and makes the final product more flexible in the event of change.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] This C++23 implementation is based on the pre C++98 implementation in the *Design Patterns* book.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] The above code depicts the creation of an interface called `IPerson` and two implementations called `Villager` and `CityPerson`.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] Based on the type passed to the `PersonFactory` object, the original concrete object is returned as the interface `IPerson`.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] A factory method is just an addition to the `PersonFactory` class.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] It creates the object of the class through interfaces but also allows the subclass to decide which class is instantiated.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] In this example, `MakeProduct` is used in `concreteFactory`.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] As a result, `MakeProduct()` may be invoked in order to retrieve it from the `IProduct`.
[src:software-design/factory-method-pattern] Custom logic could run after the object is obtained in the concrete factory method.
