[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] In computer programming, the **flyweight** software design pattern refers to an object that minimizes memory usage by sharing some of its data with other similar objects.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] The flyweight pattern is one of twenty-three *GoF design patterns*.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] In other contexts, the idea of sharing data structures is called hash consing.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] The concept was coined and first extensively explored by Paul Calder and Mark Linton in 1990 to efficiently handle glyph information in a WYSIWYG document editor.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] Similar techniques were already used in other systems, however, as early as 1988.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] The flyweight pattern is useful when dealing with a large number of objects that share simple repeated elements which would use a large amount of memory if they were individually embedded.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] It is common to hold shared data in external data structures and pass it to the objects temporarily when they are used.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] A classic example are the data structures used representing characters in a word processor.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] Naively, each character in a document might have a glyph object containing its font outline, font metrics, and other formatting data.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] However, this would use hundreds or thousands of bytes of memory for each character.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] Instead, each character can have a reference to a glyph object shared by every instance of the same character in the document.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] This way, only the position of each character needs to be stored internally.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] Clients can reuse `Flyweight` objects and pass in extrinsic state as necessary, reducing the number of physically created objects.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] After calling `operation(extrinsicState)` on the returned `Flyweight1` object, the `Client` again calls `getFlyweight(key)` on the `FlyweightFactory`.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] The `FlyweightFactory` returns the already-existing `Flyweight1` object.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] There are multiple ways to implement the flyweight pattern.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] One example is mutability: whether the objects storing extrinsic flyweight state can change.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] Immutable objects are easily shared, but require creating new extrinsic objects whenever a change in state occurs.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] In contrast, mutable objects can share state.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] Mutability allows better object reuse via the caching and re-initialization of old, unused objects.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] Sharing is usually nonviable when state is highly variable.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] Other primary concerns include retrieval (how the end-client accesses the flyweight), caching and concurrency.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] The factory interface for creating or reusing flyweight objects is often a facade for a complex underlying system.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] For example, the factory interface is commonly implemented as a singleton to provide global access for creating flyweights.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] Generally speaking, the retrieval algorithm begins with a request for a new object via the factory interface.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] The request is typically forwarded to an appropriate cache based on what kind of object it is.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] If the request is fulfilled by an object in the cache, it may be reinitialized and returned.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] Otherwise, a new object is instantiated.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] If the object is partitioned into multiple extrinsic sub-components, they will be pieced together before the object is returned.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] There are two ways to cache flyweight objects: maintained and unmaintained caches.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] Objects with highly variable state can be cached with a FIFO structure.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] This structure maintains unused objects in the cache, with no need to search the cache.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] In contrast, unmaintained caches have less upfront overhead: objects for the caches are initialized in bulk at compile time or startup.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] Once objects populate the cache, the object retrieval algorithm might have more overhead associated than the push/pop operations of a maintained cache.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] When retrieving extrinsic objects with immutable state one must simply search the cache for an object with the state one desires.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] If no such object is found, one with that state must be initialized.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] When retrieving extrinsic objects with mutable state, the cache must be searched for an unused object to reinitialize if no used object is found.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] If there is no unused object available, a new object must be instantiated and added to the cache.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] Separate caches can be used for each unique subclass of extrinsic object.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] Multiple caches can be optimized separately, associating a unique search algorithm with each cache.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] This object caching system can be encapsulated with the chain of responsibility pattern, which promotes loose coupling between components.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] Special consideration must be taken into account where flyweight objects are created on multiple threads.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] If the list of values is finite and known in advance, the flyweights can be instantiated ahead of time and retrieved from a container on multiple threads with no contention.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] Allow concurrent threads to create multiple flyweight instances, thus eliminating contention and allowing multiple instances per value.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] To enable safe sharing between clients and threads, flyweight objects can be made into immutable value objects, where two instances are considered equal if their values are equal.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] In this example, every instance of the `MyObject` class uses a `Pointer` class to provide data.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] The C++ Standard Template Library provides several containers that allow unique objects to be mapped to a key.
[src:software-design/flyweight-pattern] The use of containers helps further reduce memory usage by removing the need for temporary objects to be created.
[src:software-design/iterator-pattern] In object-oriented programming, the **iterator pattern** is a design pattern in which an iterator is used to traverse a container and access the container's elements.
[src:software-design/iterator-pattern] The iterator pattern decouples algorithms from containers; in some cases, algorithms are necessarily container-specific and thus cannot be decoupled.
[src:software-design/iterator-pattern] For example, the hypothetical algorithm `searchForElement()` can be implemented generally using a specified type of iterator rather than implementing it as a container-specific algorithm.
[src:software-design/iterator-pattern] This allows `searchForElement()` to be used on any container that supports the required type of iterator.
[src:software-design/iterator-pattern] The Iterator design pattern is one of the 23 well-known *"Gang of Four" design patterns* that describe how to solve recurring design problems to design flexible and reusable object-oriented software, that is, objects that are easier to implement, change, test, and reuse.
[src:software-design/iterator-pattern] Defining access and traversal operations in the aggregate interface is inflexible because it commits the aggregate to particular access and traversal operations and makes it impossible to add new operations later without having to change the aggregate interface.
[src:software-design/iterator-pattern] Different iterators can be used to access and traverse an aggregate in different ways.
[src:software-design/iterator-pattern] New access and traversal operations can be defined independently by defining new iterators.
[src:software-design/iterator-pattern] The essence of the Iterator Pattern is to "Provide a way to access the elements of an aggregate object sequentially without exposing its underlying representation.".
[src:software-design/iterator-pattern] In the above UML class diagram, the `Client` class refers (1) to the `Aggregate` interface for creating an `Iterator` object (`createIterator()`) and (2) to the `Iterator` interface for traversing an `Aggregate` object (`next()`, `hasNext()`).
[src:software-design/iterator-pattern] The `Iterator1` class implements the `Iterator` interface by accessing the `Aggregate1` class.
[src:software-design/iterator-pattern] The UML sequence diagram shows the run-time interactions: The `Client` object calls `createIterator()` on an `Aggregate1` object, which creates an `Iterator1` object and returns it to the `Client`.
[src:software-design/iterator-pattern] The `Client` uses then `Iterator1` to traverse the elements of the `Aggregate1` object.
[src:software-design/iterator-pattern] C++ implements iterators with the semantics of pointers in that language.
[src:software-design/iterator-pattern] In C++, a class can overload all of the pointer operations, so an iterator can be implemented that acts more or less like a pointer, complete with dereference, increment, and decrement.
[src:software-design/iterator-pattern] This has the advantage that C++ algorithms such as `std::sort` can immediately be applied to plain old memory buffers, and that there is no new syntax to learn.
[src:software-design/iterator-pattern] However, it requires an "end" iterator to test for equality, rather than allowing an iterator to know that it has reached the end.
[src:software-design/iterator-pattern] In C++ language, we say that an iterator models the iterator concept.
[src:software-design/iterator-pattern] This C++23 implementation is based on chapter "Generalizing vector yet again".
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] In software engineering, the **mediator pattern** defines an object that encapsulates how a set of objects interact.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] This pattern is considered to be a behavioral pattern due to the way it can alter the program's running behavior.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] In object-oriented programming, programs often consist of many classes.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] Business logic and computation are distributed among these classes.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] However, as more classes are added to a program, especially during maintenance and/or refactoring, the problem of communication between these classes may become more complex.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] This makes the program harder to read and maintain.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] Furthermore, it can become difficult to change the program, since any change may affect code in several other classes.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] With the mediator pattern, communication between objects is encapsulated within a **mediator object**.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] Objects no longer communicate directly with each other, but instead communicate through the mediator.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] This reduces the dependencies between communicating objects, thereby reducing coupling.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] The mediator design pattern is one of the twenty-three well-known design patterns that describe how to solve recurring design problems to design flexible and reusable object-oriented software, that is, objects that are easier to implement, change, test, and reuse.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] Defining a set of interacting objects by accessing and updating each other directly is inflexible because it tightly couples the objects to each other and makes it impossible to change the interaction independently from (without having to change) the objects.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] And it stops the objects from being reusable and makes them hard to test.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] The objects interact with each other indirectly through a mediator object that controls and coordinates the interaction.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] This makes the objects *loosely coupled*.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] They only refer to and know about their mediator object and have no explicit knowledge of each other.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] The essence of the mediator pattern is to "define an object that encapsulates how a set of objects interact".
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] It promotes loose coupling by keeping objects from referring to each other explicitly, and it allows their interaction to be varied independently.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] Client classes can use the mediator to send messages to other clients, and can receive messages from other clients via an event on the mediator class.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] In the above UML class diagram, the `Colleague1` and `Colleague2` classes do not refer to (and update) each other directly.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] Instead, they refer to the common `Mediator` interface for controlling and coordinating interaction (`mediate()`), which makes them independent from one another with respect to how the interaction is carried out.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] The `Mediator1` class implements the interaction between `Colleague1` and `Colleague2`.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] The UML sequence diagram shows the run-time interactions.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] In this example, a `Mediator1` object mediates (controls and coordinates) the interaction between `Colleague1` and `Colleague2` objects.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] Assuming that `Colleague1` wants to interact with `Colleague2` (to update/synchronize its state, for example), `Colleague1` calls `mediate(this)` on the `Mediator1` object, which gets the changed data from `Colleague1` and performs an `action2()` on `Colleague2`.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] Thereafter, `Colleague2` calls `mediate(this)` on the `Mediator1` object, which gets the changed data from `Colleague2` and performs an `action1()` on `Colleague1`.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] The mediator pattern ensures that components are loosely coupled, such that they do not call each other explicitly, but instead do so through calls to a mediator.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] In the following example, the mediator registers all Components and then calls their `SetState` methods.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] A chat room could use the mediator pattern, or a system where many ‘clients’ each receive a message each time one of the other clients performs an action (for chat rooms, this would be when each person sends a message).
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] In reality using the mediator pattern for a chat room would only be practical when used with remoting.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] Using raw sockets would not allow for the delegate callbacks (people subscribed to the Mediator class’ MessageReceived event).
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] In the following example, a `Mediator` object controls the values of several `Storage` objects, forcing the user code to access the stored values through the mediator.
[src:software-design/mediator-pattern] When a storage object wants to emit an event indicating that its value has changed, it also goes back to the mediator object (via the method `notifyObservers`) that controls the list of the observers (implemented using the observer pattern).
[src:software-design/memento-pattern] The **memento pattern** is a software design pattern in the field of object-oriented programming that allows reverting the state of an object.
[src:software-design/memento-pattern] Uses of this design pattern include undo, version control, and serialization.
[src:software-design/memento-pattern] The memento pattern is implemented with three objects: the *originator*, a *caretaker* and a *memento*.
[src:software-design/memento-pattern] The originator is some object that has an internal state.
[src:software-design/memento-pattern] The caretaker is going to do something to the originator, but wants to be able to easily bring back the prior state.
[src:software-design/memento-pattern] The caretaker first asks the originator for a memento object.
[src:software-design/memento-pattern] Then it does whatever operation (or sequence of operations) it was going to do.
[src:software-design/memento-pattern] To roll back to the state before the operations, it returns the memento object to the originator.
[src:software-design/memento-pattern] When using this pattern, care should be taken if the originator may change other objects or resources—the memento pattern operates on a single object.
[src:software-design/memento-pattern] One classic example of this pattern is the pseudorandom number generator (PRNG).
[src:software-design/memento-pattern] In this case, each consumer of the PRNG serves as a caretaker who can initialize the PRNG (the originator) with a particular seed (the memento) to produce an identical sequence of pseudorandom numbers.
[src:software-design/memento-pattern] In the above UML class diagram, the `Caretaker` class refers to the `Originator` class for saving (`createMemento()`) and restoring (`restore(memento)`) originator's internal state.
[src:software-design/memento-pattern] The `Originator` class implements (1) `createMemento()` by creating and returning a `Memento` object that stores originator's current internal state and (2) `restore(memento)` by restoring state from the passed in `Memento` object.
[src:software-design/memento-pattern] (2) Restoring originator's internal state: The `Caretaker` calls `restore(memento)` on the `Originator` object and specifies the `Memento` object that stores the state that should be restored.
[src:software-design/memento-pattern] The `Originator` gets the state (`getState()`) from the `Memento` to set its own state.
[src:software-design/memento-pattern] The following Java program illustrates the "undo" usage of the memento pattern.
[src:software-design/memento-pattern] This example uses a String as the state, which is an immutable object in Java.
[src:software-design/memento-pattern] In real-life scenarios the state will almost always be a mutable object, in which case a copy of the state must be made.
[src:software-design/memento-pattern] It must be said that the implementation shown has a drawback: it declares an internal class.
[src:software-design/memento-pattern] It would be better if this memento strategy could apply to more than one originator.
[src:software-design/memento-pattern] The object can also be accessed via a proxy, which can achieve any save/restore operation on the object.
[src:software-design/memento-pattern] The memento pattern allows one to capture the internal state of an object without violating encapsulation such that later one can undo/revert the changes if required.
[src:software-design/memento-pattern] Here one can see that the *memento object* is actually used to *revert* the changes made in the object.
[src:software-design/microservices] In software engineering, a **microservice** architecture is an architectural pattern that organizes an application into a collection of loosely coupled, fine-grained services that communicate through lightweight protocols.
[src:software-design/microservices] This pattern allows teams to develop, deploy, and scale services independently, improving modularity, scalability, and adaptability.
[src:software-design/microservices] However, it introduces additional complexity, particularly in managing distributed systems and inter-service communication, making the initial implementation more challenging compared to a monolithic architecture.
[src:software-design/microservices] There is no single, universally agreed-upon definition of microservices.
[src:software-design/microservices] However, they are generally characterized by a focus on modularity, with each service designed around a specific business capability.
[src:software-design/microservices] These services are loosely coupled, independently deployable, and often developed and scaled separately, enabling greater flexibility and agility in managing complex systems.
[src:software-design/microservices] Microservices architecture is closely associated with principles such as domain-driven design, decentralization of data and governance, and the flexibility to use different technologies for individual services to best meet their requirements.
[src:software-design/microservices] It is common for microservices architectures to be adopted for cloud-native applications, serverless computing, and applications using lightweight container deployment via OS-level virtualization.
[src:software-design/microservices] According to Fowler, because of the large number (when compared to monolithic application implementations) of services, decentralized continuous delivery and DevOps with holistic service monitoring are necessary to effectively develop, maintain, and operate such applications.
[src:software-design/microservices] A consequence of (and rationale for) following this approach is that the individual microservices can be individually scaled.
[src:software-design/microservices] In the monolithic approach, an application supporting three functions would have to be scaled in its entirety even if only one of these functions had a resource constraint.
[src:software-design/microservices] With microservices, only the microservice supporting the function with resource constraints needs to be scaled out, thus providing resource and cost optimization benefits.
[src:software-design/microservices] Despite its benefits, microservices architecture introduces challenges such as increased operational complexity, network latency, and the need for robust monitoring and fault tolerance mechanisms.
[src:software-design/microservices] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing design in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:software-design/microservices] Each cell operates independently, handling a subset of requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:software-design/microservices] A cell typically consists of multiple microservices and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:software-design/microservices] In some implementations, entire sets of microservices are replicated across multiple cells, enabling requests to be rerouted to another operational cell if one experiences a failure.
[src:software-design/microservices] This approach is intended to improve system-wide resilience by limiting the impact of localized failures.
[src:software-design/microservices] Some implementations incorporate circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:software-design/microservices] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to mitigate cascading failures among microservices, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:software-design/microservices] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in certain large-scale distributed systems where fault isolation and redundancy are design priorities.
[src:software-design/microservices] Its implementation varies based on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and specific operational goals.
[src:software-design/microservices] In 1999, software developer Peter Rodgers had been working on the Dexter research project at Hewlett Packard Labs, whose aim was to make code less brittle and to make large-scale, complex software systems robust to change.
[src:software-design/microservices] Ultimately this path of research led to the development of resource-oriented computing (ROC), a generalized computation abstraction in which REST is a special subset.
[src:software-design/microservices] In 2005, during a presentation at the Web Services Edge conference, Rodgers argued for "REST-services" and stated that "Software components are Micro-Web-Services...
[src:software-design/microservices] Micro-Services are composed using Unix-like pipelines (the Web meets Unix = true loose-coupling).
[src:software-design/microservices] Services can call services (+multiple language run-times).
[src:software-design/microservices] Complex service assemblies are abstracted behind simple URI interfaces.
[src:software-design/microservices] Also in 2005, Alistair Cockburn wrote about hexagonal architecture which is a software design pattern that is used along with the microservices.
[src:software-design/microservices] This pattern makes the design of the microservice possible since it isolates in layers the business logic from the auxiliary services needed in order to deploy and run the microservice completely independent from others.
[src:software-design/microservices] Determining the appropriate level of (micro)service granularity in a microservices architecture often requires iterative collaboration between architects and developers.
[src:software-design/microservices] This process involves evaluating user requirements, service responsibilities, and architectural characteristics, such as non-functional requirements.
[src:software-design/microservices] Neal Ford highlights the role of integrator and disintegrator factors in this context.
[src:software-design/microservices] Integrator factors, such as shared transactions or tightly coupled processes, favor combining services, while disintegrator factors, such as fault tolerance or independent scalability, encourage splitting services to meet operational and architectural goals.
[src:software-design/microservices] Additionally, fitness functions, as proposed by Neal Ford, can be used to validate architectural decisions and service granularity by continuously measuring system qualities or behaviors that are critical to stakeholders, ensuring alignment with overall architectural objectives.
[src:software-design/microservices] In microservices architectures, service granularity influences testing, deployment, performance, and reliability.
[src:software-design/microservices] Very fine-grained microservices are typically easier to test and deploy independently, but they often experience lower performance and reduced overall reliability due to increased interservice communication and more complex service choreography.
[src:software-design/microservices] Coarse-grained services exhibit contrasting characteristics.
[src:software-design/microservices] They generally provide higher robustness and reliability by minimizing communication overhead and coordination complexity, but they are more challenging to test and deploy because modifications affect a broader functional scope.
[src:software-design/microservices] The appropriate level of service granularity is determined by business drivers.
[src:software-design/microservices] Architectural decisions commonly begin with identifying these drivers and then aligning architectural characteristics such as performance, scalability, reliability, or deployment flexibility to support them.
[src:software-design/microservices] The architecture introduces additional complexity and new problems to deal with, such as latency, message format design, backup/availability/consistency (BAC), load balancing and fault tolerance.
[src:software-design/microservices] All of these problems have to be addressed at scale.
[src:software-design/microservices] The complexity of a monolithic application does not disappear if it is re-implemented as a set of microservices.
[src:software-design/microservices] Some of the complexity gets translated into operational complexity.
[src:software-design/microservices] Other places where the complexity manifests itself are increased network traffic and slower performance.
[src:software-design/microservices] Also, an application made up of any number of microservices has a larger number of interface points to access its respective ecosystem, which increases the architectural complexity.
[src:software-design/microservices] Various organizing principles (such as hypermedia as the engine of application state (HATEOAS), interface and data model documentation captured via Swagger, etc.) have been applied to reduce the impact of such additional complexity.
[src:software-design/microservices] Microservices are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing – a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:software-design/microservices] Ideally, microservices follow a "share-nothing" architecture.
[src:software-design/microservices] However, in practice, microservices architectures often encounter situations where code must be shared across services.
[src:software-design/microservices] Each approach has its advantages and trade-offs, depending on the specific context and requirements.
[src:software-design/microservices] Richards & Ford in *Fundamentals of software architecture* (2020) propose each microservice should have its own architectural characteristics (a.k.a. non functional requirements), and architects should not define uniform characteristics for the entire distributed system.
[src:software-design/microservices] To avoid having to coordinate deployments across different microservices, Sam Newman suggests keeping the interfaces of microservices stable and making backwards-compatible changes as interfaces evolve.
[src:software-design/microservices] On the topic of testing, Newman in *Building Microservices* (2015) proposes consumer-driven contract testing as a better alternative to traditional end-to-end testing in the context of microservices.
[src:software-design/microservices] He also suggests the use of log aggregation and metrics aggregation as well as distributed tracing tools to ensure the observability of systems composed of microservices.
[src:software-design/microservices] Computer microservices can be implemented in different programming languages and might use different infrastructures.
[src:software-design/microservices] Therefore, the most important technology choices are the way microservices communicate with each other (synchronous, asynchronous, UI integration) and the protocols used for the communication (e.g.
[src:software-design/microservices] In a traditional system, most technology choices like the programming language impact the whole system.
[src:software-design/microservices] Therefore, the approach to choosing technologies is quite different.
[src:software-design/microservices] The Eclipse Foundation has published a specification for developing microservices, Eclipse MicroProfile.
[src:software-design/microservices] In a service mesh, each service instance is paired with an instance of a reverse proxy server, called a service proxy, sidecar proxy, or sidecar.
[src:software-design/microservices] The service instance and sidecar proxy share a container, and the containers are managed by a container orchestration tool such as Kubernetes, Docker Swarm, or DC/OS.
[src:software-design/microservices] The service proxies are responsible for communication with other service instances and can support capabilities such as service (instance) discovery, load balancing, authentication and authorization, secure communications, and others.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] Traditionally used for desktop graphical user interfaces (GUIs), this pattern became popular for designing web applications.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] Popular programming languages have MVC frameworks that facilitate the implementation of the pattern.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] One of the seminal insights in the early development of graphical user interfaces, MVC became one of the first approaches to describe and implement software constructs in terms of their responsibilities.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] Trygve Reenskaug created MVC while working on Smalltalk-79 as a visiting scientist at the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC) in the late 1970s.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] He wanted a pattern that could be used to structure any program where users interact with a large, convoluted data set.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] His design initially had four parts: Model, view, thing, and editor.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] After discussing it with the other Smalltalk developers, he and the rest of the group settled on model, view, and controller instead.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] In their final design, a model represents some part of the program purely and intuitively.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] A view is a visual representation of a model, retrieving data from the model to display to the user and passing requests back and forth between the user and the model.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] A controller is an organizational part of the user interface that lays out and coordinates multiple Views on the screen, and which receives user input and sends the appropriate messages to its underlying Views.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] This design also includes an Editor as a specialized kind of controller used to modify a particular view, and which is created through that view.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 supports a version of MVC that evolved from this one.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] It provides abstract `view` and `controller` classes as well as various concrete subclasses of each that represent different generic widgets.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] In this scheme, a `View` represents some way of displaying information to the user, and a `controller` represents some way for the user to interact with a `view`.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] A `view` is also coupled to a model object, but the structure of that object is left up to the application programmer.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] The Smalltalk-80 environment also includes an "MVC Inspector", a development tool for viewing the structure of a given model, view, and controller side-by-side.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] In 1988, an article in *The Journal of Object Technology* (JOT) by two ex-PARC employees presented MVC as a general "programming paradigm and methodology" for Smalltalk-80 developers.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] However, their scheme differed from both Reenskaug et al.'s and that presented by the Smalltalk-80 reference books.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] They defined a view as covering any graphical concern, with a controller being a more abstract, generally invisible object that receives user input and interacts with one or many views and only one model.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] The MVC pattern subsequently evolved, giving rise to variants such as hierarchical model–view–controller (HMVC), model–view–adapter (MVA), model–view–presenter (MVP), model–view–viewmodel (MVVM), and others that adapted MVC to different contexts.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] The use of the MVC pattern in web applications grew after the introduction of NeXT's WebObjects in 1996, which was originally written in Objective-C (that borrowed heavily from Smalltalk) and helped enforce MVC principles.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] Later, the MVC pattern became popular with Java developers when WebObjects was ported to Java.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] Later frameworks for Java, such as Spring (released in October 2002), continued the strong bond between Java and MVC.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] This is close to the approach taken by the Ruby on Rails web application framework (August 2004), which has the client send requests to the server via an in-browser view, these requests are handled by a controller on the server, and the controller communicates with the appropriate model objects.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] The Django framework (July 2005, for Python) put forward a similar "model-template-view" (MTV) take on the pattern, in which a view retrieves data from models and passes it to templates for display.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] Both Rails and Django debuted with a strong emphasis on rapid deployment, which increased MVC's popularity outside the traditional enterprise environment in which it has long been popular.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] It is the application's dynamic data structure, independent of the user interface.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] It directly manages the data, logic and rules of the application.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, the design of a model type is left entirely to the programmer.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, Rails, and Django, a model type typically represents a table in the application's database.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] The model is essential for keeping the data organized and consistent.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] It ensures that the application's data behaves according to the defined rules and logic.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] Any representation of information such as a chart, diagram or table.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] Multiple views of the same information are possible, such as a bar chart for management and a tabular view for accountants.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, a view is just a visual representation of a model, and does not handle user input.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, a view represents a complete user interface element such as a menu or button, and does receive input from the user.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] In both Smalltalk-80 and WebObjects, however, views are meant to be general-purpose and composable.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, the role of the view is played by HTML templates, so in their scheme a view specifies an in-browser user interface rather than representing a user interface widget directly.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] (Django opts to call this kind of object a "template" in light of this.) This approach puts relatively less emphasis on small, composable views; a typical Rails view has a one-to-one relationship with a controller action.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 views communicate with both a model and a controller, whereas with WebObjects, a view talks only to a controller, which then talks to a model.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, a view/template is used by a controller/view when preparing a response to the client.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] Accepts input and converts it to commands for the model or view.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] A Smalltalk-80 controller handles user input events, such as button presses or mouse movement.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] At any given time, each controller has one associated view and model, although one model object may hear from many different controllers.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] Only one controller, the "active" controller, receives user input at any given time; a global window manager object is responsible for setting the current active controller.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] If user input prompts a change in a model, the controller will signal the model to change, but the model is then responsible for telling its views to update.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] In WebObjects, the views handle user input, and the controller mediates between the views and the models.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] There may be only one controller per application, or one controller per window.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] Much of the application-specific logic is found in the controller.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] In Rails, requests arriving at the on-server application from the client are sent to a "router", which maps the request to a specific method of a specific controller.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] Within that method, the controller interacts with the request data and any relevant model objects and prepares a response using a view.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] Conventionally, each view has an associated controller; for example, if the application had a `client` view, it would typically have an associated `Clients` controller as well.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] However, developers are free to make other kinds of controllers if they wish.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] Django calls the object playing this role a "view" instead of a controller.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] A Django view is a function that receives a web request and returns a web response.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] It may use templates to create the response.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] As with other software patterns, MVC expresses the "core of the solution" to a problem while allowing it to be adapted for each system.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] Particular MVC designs can vary significantly from the traditional description here.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] As Alan Kay wrote in 2003, the original motivation behind the MVC was to allow creation of a graphical interface for any object.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] That was outlined in detail in Richard Pawson's book *Naked Objects*.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] Although originally developed for desktop computing, MVC has been widely adopted as a design for World Wide Web applications in major programming languages.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] Several web frameworks have been created that enforce the pattern.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] These software frameworks vary in their interpretations, mainly in the way that the MVC responsibilities are divided between the client and server.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] Early MVC frameworks took a thin client approach that placed almost the entire model, view and controller logic on the server.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] In this approach, the client sends hyperlink requests or form submissions to the controller and then receives a complete and updated web page (or other document) from the view; the model exists entirely on the server.
[src:software-design/model-view-controller] Later frameworks have allowed the MVC components to execute partly on the client, using Ajax to synchronize data.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] The subject knows its observers through a standardized interface and manages the subscription list directly.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] This pattern creates a one-to-many dependency where multiple observers can listen to a single subject, but the coupling is typically synchronous and direct—the subject calls observer methods when changes occur, though asynchronous implementations using event queues are possible.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] Unlike the publish-subscribe pattern, there is no intermediary broker; the subject and observers have direct references to each other.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] It is commonly used to implement event handling systems in event-driven programming, particularly in-process systems like GUI toolkits or MVC frameworks.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] This makes the pattern well-suited to processing data that arrives unpredictably—such as user input, HTTP requests, GPIO signals, updates from distributed databases, or changes in a GUI model.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] The observer design pattern is a behavioural pattern listed among the 23 well-known "Gang of Four" design patterns that address recurring design challenges in order to design flexible and reusable object-oriented software, yielding objects that are easier to implement, change, test, and reuse.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] The naive approach would be for one object (subject) to directly call specific methods on each dependent object.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] This creates tight coupling because the subject must know the concrete types and specific interfaces of all dependent objects, making the code inflexible and hard to extend.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] However, this direct approach may be preferable in performance-critical scenarios (such as low-level kernel structures or real-time systems) where the overhead of abstraction is unacceptable and compile-time optimization is crucial.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] When a subject changes state, all registered observers are notified and updated automatically.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] The subject manages its own state while also maintaining a list of observers and notifying them of state changes by calling their `update()` operation.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] The responsibility of observers is to register and unregister themselves with a subject (in order to be notified of state changes) and to update their state (to synchronize it with the subject's state) when they are notified.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] This approach makes subject and observers loosely coupled through interface standardization.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] The subject only needs to know that observers implement the `update()` method—it has no knowledge of observers' concrete types or internal implementation details.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] Observers can be added and removed independently at run time.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] The observer pattern and the publish–subscribe pattern are closely related and often confused, as both support one-to-many communication between components.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] However, they differ significantly in architecture, degree of coupling, and common use cases.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] In practice, publish–subscribe systems evolved to address several limitations of the observer pattern.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] A typical observer implementation creates a tight coupling between the subject and its observers.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] This may limit scalability, flexibility, and maintainability, especially in distributed environments.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] Subjects and observers must conform to a shared interface, and both parties are aware of each other’s presence.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] To reduce this coupling, publish–subscribe systems introduce a message broker or event bus that intermediates between publishers and subscribers.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] This additional layer removes the need for direct references, allowing systems to evolve independently.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] Brokers may also support features like message persistence, delivery guarantees, topic-based filtering, and asynchronous communication.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] In some systems, the observer pattern is used internally to implement subscription mechanisms behind a publish–subscribe interface.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] In other cases, the patterns are applied independently.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] For example, JavaScript libraries and frameworks often offer both observer-like subscriptions (e.g., via callback registration) and decoupled pub-sub mechanisms (e.g., via event emitters or signals).
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] Historically, in early graphical operating systems like OS/2 and Microsoft Windows, the terms "publish–subscribe" and "event-driven programming" were often used as synonyms for the observer pattern.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] The observer pattern, as formalized in *Design Patterns*, deliberately omits concerns such as unsubscription, notification filtering, delivery guarantees, and message logging.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] These advanced capabilities are typically implemented in robust message queuing systems, where the observer pattern may serve as a foundational mechanism but is not sufficient by itself.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] Related patterns include mediator and singleton.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] A common drawback of the observer pattern is the potential for memory leaks, known as the lapsed listener problem.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] This occurs when a subject maintains strong references to its observers, preventing them from being garbage collected even if they are no longer needed elsewhere.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] Because the pattern typically requires both explicit registration and deregistration (as in the dispose pattern), forgetting to unregister observers can leave dangling references.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] This issue can be mitigated by using weak references for observer references, allowing the garbage collector to reclaim observer objects that are no longer in use.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] In some applications, particularly user interfaces, the subject's state may change so frequently that notifying observers on every change is inefficient or counterproductive.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] For example, a view that re-renders on every minor change in a data model might become unresponsive or flicker.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] In such cases, the observer pattern can be modified to decouple notifications *temporally* by introducing a throttling mechanism, such as a timer.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] Rather than updating on every state change, the observer polls the subject or is notified at regular intervals, rendering an approximate but stable view of the model.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] This approach is commonly used for elements like progress bars, where the underlying process changes state rapidly.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] Instead of responding to every minor increment, the observer updates the visual display periodically, improving performance and usability.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] This form of temporal decoupling allows observers to remain responsive without being overwhelmed by high-frequency updates, while still reflecting the overall trend or progress of the subject’s state.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] In this UML class diagram, the `Subject` class does not update the state of dependent objects directly.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] Instead, `Subject` refers to the `Observer` interface (`update()`) for updating state, which makes the `Subject` independent of how the state of dependent objects is updated.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] The `Observer1` and `Observer2` classes implement the `Observer` interface by synchronizing their state with subject's state.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] The UML sequence diagram shows the runtime interactions: The `Observer1` and `Observer2` objects call `attach(this)` on `Subject1` to register themselves.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] Assuming that the state of `Subject1` changes, `Subject1` calls `notify()` on itself.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] `notify()` calls `update()` on the registered `Observer1` and `Observer2`objects, which request the changed data (`getState()`) from `Subject1` to update (synchronize) their state.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] While the library classes `java.util.Observer` and `java.util.Observable` exist, they have been deprecated in Java 9 because the model implemented was quite limited.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] Below is an example written in Java that takes keyboard input and handles each input line as an event.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] When a string is supplied from `System.in`, the method `notifyObservers()` is then called in order to notify all observers of the event's occurrence, in the form of an invocation of their update methods.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] C# provides the `IObservable`. and `IObserver` interfaces as well as documentation on how to implement the design pattern.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] JavaScript has a deprecated `Object.observe` function that was a more accurate implementation of the observer pattern.
[src:software-design/observer-pattern] This would fire events upon change to the observed object.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] The **prototype pattern** is a creational design pattern in software development.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] It is used when the types of objects to create is determined by a prototypical instance, which is cloned to produce new objects.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] This pattern is used to avoid subclasses of an object creator in the client application, like the factory method pattern does, and to avoid the inherent cost of creating a new object in the standard way (e.g., using the 'new' keyword) when it is prohibitively expensive for a given application.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] To implement the pattern, the client declares an abstract base class that specifies a pure virtual *clone()* method.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] Any class that needs a "polymorphic constructor" capability derives itself from the abstract base class, and implements the *clone()* operation.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] The mitotic division of a cell — resulting in two identical cells — is an example of a prototype that plays an active role in copying itself and thus, demonstrates the Prototype pattern.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] When a cell splits, two cells of identical genotype result.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] The prototype design pattern is one of the 23 Gang of Four design patterns that describe how to solve recurring design problems to design flexible and reusable object-oriented software, that is, objects that are easier to implement, change, test, and reuse.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] Creating objects directly within the class that requires (uses) the objects is inflexible because it commits the class to particular objects at compile-time and makes it impossible to specify which objects to create at run-time.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] This enables configuration of a class with different `Prototype` objects, which are copied to create new objects, and even more, `Prototype` objects can be added and removed at run-time.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] In the above UML class diagram, the `Client` class refers to the `Prototype` interface for cloning a `Product`.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] The `Product1` class implements the `Prototype` interface by creating a copy of itself.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] The UML sequence diagram shows the run-time interactions: The `Client` object calls `clone()` on a `prototype:Product1` object, which creates and returns a copy of itself (a `product:Product1` object).
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] Sometimes creational patterns overlap—there are cases when either prototype or abstract factory would be appropriate.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] At other times, they complement each other: abstract factory might store a set of prototypes from which to clone and return product objects.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] Abstract factory, builder, and prototype can use singleton in their implementations.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] Abstract factory classes are often implemented with factory methods (creation through inheritance), but they can be implemented using prototype (creation through delegation).
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] Often, designs start out using Factory Method (less complicated, more customizable, subclasses proliferate) and evolve toward abstract factory, prototype, or builder (more flexible, more complex) as the designer discovers where more flexibility is needed.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] Prototype does not require subclassing, but it does require an "initialize" operation.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] Factory method requires subclassing, but does not require initialization.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] Designs that make heavy use of the composite and decorator patterns often can benefit from Prototype as well.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] A general guideline in programming suggests using the `clone()` method when creating a duplicate object during runtime to ensure it accurately reflects the original object.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] This process, known as object cloning, produces a new object with identical attributes to the one being cloned.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] Alternatively, *instantiating* a class using the `new` keyword generates an object with default attribute values.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] For instance, in the context of designing a system for managing bank account transactions, it may be necessary to duplicate the object containing account information to conduct transactions while preserving the original data.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] In such scenarios, employing the `clone()` method is preferable over using `new` to instantiate a new object.
[src:software-design/prototype-pattern] Discussion of the design pattern along with a complete illustrative example implementation using polymorphic class design are provided in the C++ Annotations.
[src:software-design/proxy-pattern] In computer programming, the **proxy pattern** is a software design pattern which is a class functioning as an interface to something else.
[src:software-design/proxy-pattern] The proxy could interface to anything: a network connection, a large object in memory, a file, or some other resource that is expensive or impossible to duplicate.
[src:software-design/proxy-pattern] In short, a proxy is a wrapper or agent object that is being called by the client to access the real serving object behind the scenes.
[src:software-design/proxy-pattern] Use of the proxy can simply be forwarding to the real object, or can provide additional logic.
[src:software-design/proxy-pattern] In the proxy, extra functionality can be provided, for example caching when operations on the real object are resource intensive, or checking preconditions before operations on the real object are invoked.
[src:software-design/proxy-pattern] For the client, usage of a proxy object is similar to using the real object, because both implement the same interface.
[src:software-design/proxy-pattern] The proxy design pattern is one of the twenty-three well-known *GoF design patterns* that describe how to solve recurring design problems to design flexible and reusable object-oriented software, that is, objects that are easier to implement, change, test, and reuse.
[src:software-design/proxy-pattern] When accessing sensitive objects, for example, it should be possible to check that clients have the needed access rights.
[src:software-design/proxy-pattern] This makes it possible to work through a `Proxy` object to perform additional functionality when accessing a subject, like checking the access rights of clients accessing a sensitive object.
[src:software-design/proxy-pattern] To act as a substitute for a subject, a proxy must implement the `Subject` interface.
[src:software-design/proxy-pattern] Clients can't tell whether they work with a subject or its proxy.
[src:software-design/proxy-pattern] In the above UML class diagram, the `Proxy` class implements the `Subject` interface so that it can act as substitute for `Subject` objects.
[src:software-design/proxy-pattern] It maintains a reference (`realSubject`) to the substituted object (`RealSubject`) so that it can forward requests to it (`realSubject.operation()`).
[src:software-design/proxy-pattern] The sequence diagram shows the run-time interactions: The `Client` object works through a `Proxy` object that controls the access to a `RealSubject` object.
[src:software-design/proxy-pattern] In this example, the `Proxy` forwards the request to the `RealSubject`, which performs the request.
[src:software-design/proxy-pattern] In distributed object communication, a local object represents a remote object (one that belongs to a different address space).
[src:software-design/proxy-pattern] The local object is a proxy for the remote object, and method invocation on the local object results in remote method invocation on the remote object.
[src:software-design/proxy-pattern] An example would be an ATM implementation, where the ATM might hold proxy objects for bank information that exists in the remote server.
[src:software-design/proxy-pattern] In place of a complex or heavy object, a skeleton representation may be advantageous in some cases.
[src:software-design/proxy-pattern] When an underlying image is huge in size, it may be represented using a virtual proxy object, loading the real object on demand.
[src:software-design/proxy-pattern] A protection proxy might be used to control access to a resource based on access rights.
[src:software-design/singleton-pattern] In object-oriented programming, the **singleton pattern** is a software design pattern that restricts the instantiation of a class to a singular instance.
[src:software-design/singleton-pattern] It is one of the well-known "Gang of Four" design patterns, which describe how to solve recurring problems in object-oriented software.
[src:software-design/singleton-pattern] The pattern is useful when exactly one object is needed to coordinate actions across a system.
[src:software-design/singleton-pattern] The term comes from the mathematical concept of a singleton.
[src:software-design/singleton-pattern] Singletons are often preferred to global variables because they do not pollute the global namespace (or their containing namespace).
[src:software-design/singleton-pattern] Additionally, they permit lazy allocation and initialization, whereas global variables in many languages will always consume resources.
[src:software-design/singleton-pattern] The singleton pattern can also be used as a basis for other design patterns, such as the abstract factory, factory method, builder and prototype patterns.
[src:software-design/singleton-pattern] Facade objects are also often singletons because only one facade object is required.
[src:software-design/singleton-pattern] Logging is a common real-world use case for singletons, because all objects that wish to log messages require a uniform point of access and conceptually write to a single source.
[src:software-design/singleton-pattern] Implementations of the singleton pattern ensure that only one instance of the singleton class ever exists and typically provide global access to that instance.
[src:software-design/singleton-pattern] The instance is usually stored as a private static variable; the instance is created when the variable is initialized, at some point before when the static method is first called.
[src:software-design/singleton-pattern] This C++23 implementation is based on the pre-C++98 implementation in the book .
[src:software-design/singleton-pattern] This is an implementation of the Meyers singleton in C++11.
[src:software-design/singleton-pattern] The Meyers singleton has no destruct method.
[src:software-design/singleton-pattern] The program output is the same as above.
[src:software-design/singleton-pattern] A singleton implementation may use lazy initialization in which the instance is created when the static method is first invoked.
[src:software-design/singleton-pattern] In multithreaded programs, this can cause race conditions that result in the creation of multiple instances.
[src:software-design/singleton-pattern] The following Java 5+ example is a thread-safe implementation, using lazy initialization with double-checked locking.
[src:software-design/singleton-pattern] Some consider the singleton to be an anti-pattern that introduces global state into an application, often unnecessarily.
[src:software-design/singleton-pattern] This introduces a potential dependency on the singleton by other objects, requiring analysis of implementation details to determine whether a dependency actually exists.
[src:software-design/singleton-pattern] This increased coupling can introduce difficulties with unit testing.
[src:software-design/singleton-pattern] In turn, this places restrictions on any abstraction that uses the singleton, such as preventing concurrent use of multiple instances.
[src:software-design/singleton-pattern] Singletons also violate the single-responsibility principle because they are responsible for enforcing their own uniqueness along with performing their normal functions.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] A **software design pattern** describes a reusable solution to a commonly needed behavior in software.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] A design pattern is not a rigid structure to be copied directly into source code.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Rather, it is a description of and a template for solving a particular type of problem that can be used in many different contexts, including different programming languages and computing platforms.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Design patterns can be viewed as formalized best practices that the programmer may use to solve common problems when designing software.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Object-oriented design patterns typically show relationships and interactions between classes or objects, without specifying the final application classes or objects that are involved.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Patterns that imply mutable state may be unsuited for functional programming languages.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Some patterns can be rendered unnecessary in languages that have built-in support for solving the problem they are trying to solve, and object-oriented patterns are not necessarily suitable for non-object-oriented languages.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Patterns originated as an architectural concept by Christopher Alexander as early as 1977 in A Pattern Language (cf. his article, "The Pattern of Streets," JOURNAL OF THE AIP, September, 1966, Vol.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] In 1987, Kent Beck and Ward Cunningham began experimenting with the idea of applying patterns to programming – specifically pattern languages – and presented their results at the OOPSLA conference that year.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] In the following years, Beck, Cunningham and others followed up on this work.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Design patterns gained popularity in computer science after the book *Design Patterns: Elements of Reusable Object-Oriented Software* was published in 1994 by the so-called "Gang of Four" (Erich Gamma, Richard Helm, Ralph Johnson and John Vlissides), which is frequently abbreviated as "GoF".
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] That same year, the first Pattern Languages of Programming Conference was held, and the following year the Portland Pattern Repository was set up for documentation of design patterns.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Although design patterns have been applied practically for a long time, formalization of the concept of design patterns languished for several years.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Design patterns can speed up the development process by providing proven development paradigms.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Effective software design requires considering issues that may not become apparent until later in the implementation.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Freshly written code can often have hidden, subtle issues that take time to be detected – issues that sometimes can cause major problems down the road.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Reusing design patterns can help to prevent such issues, and enhance code readability for those familiar with the patterns.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Software design techniques are difficult to apply to a broader range of problems.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Design patterns provide general solutions, documented in a format that does not require specifics tied to a particular problem.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] In 1996, Christopher Alexander was invited to give a Keynote Speech to the 1996 OOPSLA Convention.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Here he reflected on how his work on Patterns in Architecture had developed and his hopes for how the Software Design community could help Architecture extend Patterns to create living structures that use generative schemes that are more like computer code.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] A pattern describes a *design motif*, also known as a *prototypical micro-architecture*, as a set of program constituents (e.g., classes, methods...) and their relationships.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] A developer adapts the motif to their codebase to solve the problem described by the pattern.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] The resulting code has structure and organization similar to the chosen motif.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Efforts have also been made to codify design patterns in particular domains, including the use of existing design patterns as well as domain-specific design patterns.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Examples include user interface design patterns, information visualization, secure design, "secure usability", web design and business model design.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] The annual Pattern Languages of Programming Conference proceedings include many examples of domain-specific patterns.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Design patterns can be organized into groups based on what kind of problem they solve.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] A structural pattern organizes classes and objects to form larger structures that provide new functionality.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] A behavioral pattern describes collaboration between objects.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] A concurrency pattern supports concurrent processing.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] The documentation for a design pattern describes the context in which the pattern is used, the forces within the context that the pattern seeks to resolve, and the suggested solution.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] There is no single, standard format for documenting design patterns.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Rather, a variety of different formats have been used by different pattern authors.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] However, according to Martin Fowler, certain pattern forms have become more well-known than others, and consequently become common starting points for new pattern-writing efforts.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] One example of a commonly used documentation format is the one used by Erich Gamma, Richard Helm, Ralph Johnson, and John Vlissides in their book *Design Patterns*.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] A descriptive and unique name that helps in identifying and referring to the pattern.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] A description of the goal behind the pattern and the reason for using it.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] A scenario consisting of a problem and a context in which this pattern can be used.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Situations in which this pattern is usable; the context for the pattern.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] A graphical representation of the pattern.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] A listing of the classes and objects used in the pattern and their roles in the design.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] A description of how classes and objects used in the pattern interact with each other.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] A description of the results, side effects, and trade offs caused by using the pattern.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] A description of an implementation of the pattern; the solution part of the pattern.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] An illustration of how the pattern can be used in a programming language.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Other patterns that have some relationship with the pattern; discussion of the differences between the pattern and similar patterns.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Some suggest that the need for a design pattern may be a sign that a feature is missing from a programming language.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Peter Norvig demonstrates that 16 out of the 23 patterns in the *Design Patterns* book (which is primarily focused on C++) are simplified or eliminated (via direct language support) in Lisp or Dylan.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] See also Paul Graham's essay "Revenge of the Nerds".
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Inappropriate use of patterns may unnecessarily increase complexity.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] By definition, a pattern must be programmed anew into each application that uses it.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Since some authors see this as a step backward from software reuse as provided by components, researchers have worked to use generic programming facilities to turn patterns into components, in a process called *componentization*.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Meyer & Arnout (2006) were able to provide full or partial componentization of two-thirds of the patterns they attempted.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] In order to achieve flexibility, design patterns may introduce additional levels of indirection, which may complicate the resulting design and decrease runtime performance.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] A reusable, proven solution to a recurring problem at the system level, addressing concerns related to the overall structure, component interactions, and quality attributes of the system.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Software architecture patterns operate at a higher level of abstraction than design patterns, solving broader system-level challenges.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] While these patterns typically affect system-level concerns, the distinction between architectural patterns and architectural styles can sometimes be blurry.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] A high-level, structural organization that defines the overall system organization, specifying how components are organized, how they interact, and the constraints on those interactions.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] Architecture styles typically include a vocabulary of component and connector types, as well as semantic models for interpreting the system's properties.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] These styles represent the most coarse-grained level of system organization.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] , which are often limited to a single class.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] which does not introduce an abstraction, and so which resides at the level of implementation details.
[src:software-design/software-design-pattern] although in other languages, such idioms may constitute true design patterns.
[src:software-design/solid] In object-oriented programming and functional programming, **SOLID** is a mnemonic acronym for five principles intended to make source code more understandable, flexible, and maintainable.
[src:software-design/solid] Although the principles apply to object-oriented programming, they also form a core philosophy for methodologies such as agile software development and adaptive software development.
[src:software-design/solid] Software engineer and instructor Robert C.
[src:software-design/solid] Martin introduced the basic principles of SOLID design in his 2000 paper *Design Principles and Design Patterns* about software rot.
[src:software-design/solid] The *SOLID* acronym was coined around 2004 by Michael Feathers.
[src:software-design/solid] The single-responsibility principle (SRP) states that there should never be more than one reason for a class to change.
[src:software-design/solid] In other words, every class should have only one responsibility.
[src:software-design/solid] The open–closed principle (OCP) states that software entities should be open for extension, but closed for modification.
[src:software-design/solid] The Liskov substitution principle (LSP) states that functions that use pointers or references to base classes must be able to use pointers or references of derived classes without knowing it.
[src:software-design/solid] The interface segregation principle (ISP) states that clients should not be forced to depend upon interface methods that they do not use.
[src:software-design/solid] The dependency inversion principle (DIP) states that one should depend upon abstractions, not concretes.
[src:software-design/state-pattern] The **state pattern** is a behavioral software design pattern that allows an object to alter its behavior when its internal state changes.
[src:software-design/state-pattern] This pattern is close to the concept of finite-state machines.
[src:software-design/state-pattern] The state pattern can be interpreted as a strategy pattern, which is able to switch a strategy through invocations of methods defined in the pattern's interface.
[src:software-design/state-pattern] The state pattern is used in computer programming to encapsulate varying behavior for the same object, based on its internal state.
[src:software-design/state-pattern] This can be a cleaner way for an object to change its behavior at runtime without resorting to conditional statements and thus improve maintainability.
[src:software-design/state-pattern] The state design pattern is one of twenty-three design patterns documented by the Gang of Four that describe how to solve recurring design problems.
[src:software-design/state-pattern] Such problems cover the design of flexible and reusable object-oriented software, such as objects that are easy to implement, change, test, and reuse.
[src:software-design/state-pattern] Implementing state-specific behavior directly within a class is inflexible because it commits the class to a particular behavior and makes it impossible to add a new state or change the behavior of an existing state later, independently from the class, without changing the class.
[src:software-design/state-pattern] This makes a class independent of how state-specific behavior is implemented.
[src:software-design/state-pattern] New states can be added by defining new state classes.
[src:software-design/state-pattern] A class can change its behavior at run-time by changing its current state object.
[src:software-design/state-pattern] In the accompanying Unified Modeling Language (UML) class diagram, the `Context` class doesn't implement state-specific behavior directly.
[src:software-design/state-pattern] Instead, `Context` refers to the `State` interface for performing state-specific behavior (`state.handle()`), which makes `Context` independent of how state-specific behavior is implemented.
[src:software-design/state-pattern] The `ConcreteStateA` and `ConcreteStateB` classes implement the `State` interface, that is, implement (encapsulate) the state-specific behavior for each state.
[src:software-design/state-pattern] The `Context` object delegates state-specific behavior to different `State` objects.
[src:software-design/state-pattern] First, `Context` calls `handle(this)` on its current (initial) state object (`ConcreteStateA`), which performs the operation and calls `setState(ConcreteStateB)` on `Context` to change context's current state to `ConcreteStateB`.
[src:software-design/state-pattern] The next time, `Context` again calls `handle(this)` on its current state object (`ConcreteStateB`), which performs the operation and changes context's current state to `ConcreteStateA`.
[src:software-design/state-pattern] This is a C++ example demonstrating the state pattern.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] In computer programming, the **strategy pattern** (also known as the **policy pattern**) is a behavioral software design pattern that enables selecting an algorithm at runtime.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] Instead of implementing a single algorithm directly, code receives runtime instructions as to which in a family of algorithms to use.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] Strategy lets the algorithm vary independently from clients that use it.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] Strategy is one of the patterns included in the influential book *Design Patterns* by Gamma et al. that popularized the concept of using design patterns to describe how to design flexible and reusable object-oriented software.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] Deferring the decision about which algorithm to use until runtime allows the calling code to be more flexible and reusable.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] For instance, a class that performs validation on incoming data may use the strategy pattern to select a validation algorithm depending on the type of data, the source of the data, user choice, or other discriminating factors.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] These factors are not known until runtime and may require radically different validation to be performed.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] The validation algorithms (strategies), encapsulated separately from the validating object, may be used by other validating objects in different areas of the system (or even different systems) without code duplication.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] Typically, the strategy pattern stores a reference to code in a data structure and retrieves it.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] This can be achieved by mechanisms such as the native function pointer, the first-class function, classes or class instances in object-oriented programming languages, or accessing the language implementation's internal storage of code via reflection.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] In the above UML class diagram, the `Context` class does not implement an algorithm directly.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] Instead, `Context` refers to the `Strategy` interface for performing an algorithm (`strategy.algorithm()`), which makes `Context` independent of how an algorithm is implemented.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] The `Strategy1` and `Strategy2` classes implement the `Strategy` interface, that is, implement (encapsulate) an algorithm.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] The UML sequence diagram shows the runtime interactions: The `Context` object delegates an algorithm to different `Strategy` objects.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] First, `Context` calls `algorithm()` on a `Strategy1` object, which performs the algorithm and returns the result to `Context`.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] Thereafter, `Context` changes its strategy and calls `algorithm()` on a `Strategy2` object, which performs the algorithm and returns the result to `Context`.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] According to the strategy pattern, the behaviors of a class should not be inherited.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] Instead, they should be encapsulated using interfaces.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] This is compatible with the open–closed principle (OCP), which proposes that classes should be open for extension but closed for modification.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] Two possible functionalities for car are *brake* and *accelerate*.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] Since accelerate and brake behaviors change frequently between models, a common approach is to implement these behaviors in subclasses.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] This approach has significant drawbacks; accelerate and brake behaviors must be declared in each new car model.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] The work of managing these behaviors increases greatly as the number of models increases, and requires code to be duplicated across models.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] Additionally, it is not easy to determine the exact nature of the behavior for each model without investigating the code in each.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] The strategy pattern uses composition instead of inheritance.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] In the strategy pattern, behaviors are defined as separate interfaces and specific classes that implement these interfaces.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] This allows better decoupling between the behavior and the class that uses the behavior.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] The behavior can be changed without breaking the classes that use it, and the classes can switch between behaviors by changing the specific implementation used without requiring any significant code changes.
[src:software-design/strategy-pattern] Behaviors can also be changed at runtime as well as at design-time.
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] In object-oriented programming, the **template method** is one of the behavioral design patterns identified by Gamma et al. in the book *Design Patterns*.
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] The template method is a method in a superclass, usually an abstract superclass, and defines the skeleton of an operation in terms of a number of high-level steps.
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] These steps are themselves implemented by additional *helper methods* in the same class as the *template method*.
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] The *helper methods* may be either *abstract methods*, in which case subclasses are required to provide concrete implementations, or *hook methods,* which have empty bodies in the superclass.
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] Subclasses can (but are not required to) customize the operation by overriding the hook methods.
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] The intent of the template method is to define the overall structure of the operation, while allowing subclasses to refine, or redefine, certain steps.
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] At run-time, the algorithm represented by the template method is executed by sending the template message to an instance of one of the concrete subclasses.
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] Through inheritance, the template method in the base class starts to execute.
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] When the template method sends a message to self requesting one of the helper methods, the message will be received by the concrete sub-instance.
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] If the helper method has been overridden, the overriding implementation in the sub-instance will execute; if it has not been overridden, the inherited implementation in the base class will execute.
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] This mechanism ensures that the overall algorithm follows the same steps every time while allowing the details of some steps to depend on which instance received the original request to execute the algorithm.
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] This pattern is an example of inversion of control because the high-level code no longer determines what algorithms to run; a lower-level algorithm is instead selected at run-time.
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] Some of the self-messages sent by the template method may be to *hook methods.* These methods are implemented in the same base class as the template method, but with empty bodies (i.e., they do nothing).
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] Hook methods exist so that subclasses can override them, and can thus fine-tune the action of the algorithm *without* the need to override the template method itself.
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] In other words, they provide a "hook" on which to "hang" variant implementations.
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] The *template method* is used in frameworks, where each implements the invariant parts of a domain's architecture, while providing hook methods for customization.
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] This is an example of inversion of control.
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] The template method is used for the following reasons.
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] The template pattern is useful when working with auto-generated code.
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] The challenge of working with generated code is that changes to the source code will lead to changes in the generated code; if hand-written modifications have been made to the generated code, these will be lost.
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] How, then, should the generated code be customized?
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] The Template pattern provides a solution.
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] If the generated code follows the template method pattern, the generated code will all be an abstract superclass.
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] Provided that hand-written customizations are confined to a subclass, the code generator can be run again without risk of over-writing these modifications.
[src:software-design/template-method-pattern] When used with code generation, this pattern is sometimes referred to as the generation gap pattern.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] A **visitor pattern** is a software design pattern that separates the algorithm from the object structure.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] Because of this separation, new operations can be added to existing object structures without modifying the structures.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] It is one way to follow the open/closed principle in object-oriented programming and software engineering.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] In essence, the visitor allows adding new virtual functions to a family of classes, without modifying the classes.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] Instead, a visitor class is created that implements all of the appropriate specializations of the virtual function.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] The visitor takes the instance reference as input, and implements the goal through double dispatch.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] Programming languages with sum types and pattern matching obviate many of the benefits of the visitor pattern, as the visitor class is able to both easily branch on the type of the object and generate a compiler error if a new object type is defined which the visitor does not yet handle.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] The Visitor design pattern is one of the twenty-three *Gang of Four design patterns*.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] This makes it possible to create new operations independently from the classes of an object structure by adding new visitor objects.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] The nature of the Visitor makes it an ideal pattern to plug into public APIs, thus allowing its clients to perform operations on a class using a "visiting" class without having to modify the source.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] A drawback to this pattern, however, is that it makes extensions to the class hierarchy more difficult, as new classes typically require a new `visit` method to be added to each visitor.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] Consider the design of a 2D computer-aided design (CAD) system.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] At its core, there are several types to represent basic geometric shapes like circles, lines, and arcs.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] The entities are ordered into layers, and at the top of the type hierarchy is the drawing, which is simply a list of layers, plus some added properties.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] A fundamental operation on this type hierarchy is saving a drawing to the system's native file format.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] At first glance, it may seem desirable to add local save methods to all types in the hierarchy.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] But it can also be useful to save drawings to other file formats.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] Adding ever more methods for saving into many different file formats can complicate the original geometric data structure.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] A naive way to solve this would be to maintain separate functions for each file format.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] Such a save function would take a drawing as input, traverse it, and encode into that specific file format.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] As this is done for each added different format, duplication between the functions accumulates.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] For example, saving a circle shape in a raster format requires very similar code no matter what specific raster form is used, and is different from other primitive shapes.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] The case for other primitive shapes like lines and polygons is similar.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] Thus, the code becomes a large outer loop traversing through the objects, with a large decision tree inside the loop querying the type of the object.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] Another problem with this approach is that it is very easy to miss a shape in one or more savers, or a new primitive shape is introduced, but the save routine is implemented only for one file type and not others, leading to code extension and maintenance problems.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] As the versions of the same file grows it becomes more complicated to maintain it.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] Instead, the visitor pattern can be applied.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] It encodes the logical operation (i.e. save(image_tree)) on the whole hierarchy into one class (i.e.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] Saver) that implements the common methods for traversing the tree and describes virtual helper methods (i.e. save_circle, save_square, etc.) to be implemented for format specific behaviors.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] In the case of the CAD example, such format specific behaviors would be implemented by a subclass of Visitor (i.e.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] As such, all duplication of type checks and traversal steps is removed.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] Additionally, the compiler now complains if a shape is omitted since it is now expected by the common base traversal/save function.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] The visitor pattern may be used for iteration over container-like data structures just like Iterator pattern but with limited functionality.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] For example, iteration over a directory structure could be implemented by a function class instead of more conventional loop pattern.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] This would allow deriving various useful information from directories content by implementing a visitor functionality for every item while reusing the iteration code.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] It's widely employed in Smalltalk systems and can be found in C++ as well.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] A drawback of this approach, however, is that you can't break out of the loop easily or iterate concurrently (in parallel i.e. traversing two containers at the same time by a single `i` variable).
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] The latter would require writing additional functionality for a visitor to support these features.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] In the UML class diagram above, the `ElementA` class doesn't implement a new operation directly.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] Instead, `ElementA` implements a *dispatching operation* `accept(visitor)` that "dispatches" (delegates) a request to the "accepted visitor object" (`visitor.visitElementA(this)`).
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] The `Visitor1` class implements the operation (`visitElementA(e:ElementA)`).
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] `ElementB` then implements `accept(visitor)` by dispatching to `visitor.visitElementB(this)`.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] The `Visitor1` class implements the operation (`visitElementB(e:ElementB)`).
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] The UML sequence diagram shows the run-time interactions: The `Client` object traverses the elements of an object structure (`ElementA,ElementB`) and calls `accept(visitor)` on each element.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] First, the `Client` calls `accept(visitor)` on `ElementA`, which calls `visitElementA(this)` on the accepted `visitor` object.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] The element itself (`this`) is passed to the `visitor` so that it can "visit" `ElementA` (call `operationA()`).
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] Thereafter, the `Client` calls `accept(visitor)` on `ElementB`, which calls `visitElementB(this)` on the `visitor` that "visits" `ElementB` (calls `operationB()`).
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] The visitor pattern requires a programming language that supports single dispatch, as common object-oriented languages (such as C++, Java, Smalltalk, Objective-C, Swift, JavaScript, Python and C#) do.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] Under this condition, consider two objects, each of some class type; one is termed the *element*, and the other is *visitor*.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] The *visitor* declares a `visit` method, which takes the element as an argument, for each class of element.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] *Concrete visitors* are derived from the visitor class and implement these `visit` methods, each of which implements part of the algorithm operating on the object structure.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] The state of the algorithm is maintained locally by the concrete visitor class.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] The *element* declares an `accept` method to accept a visitor, taking the visitor as an argument.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] *Concrete elements*, derived from the element class, implement the `accept` method.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] In its simplest form, this is no more than a call to the visitor's `visit` method.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] Composite elements, which maintain a list of child objects, typically iterate over these, calling each child's `accept` method.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] The *client* creates the object structure, directly or indirectly, and instantiates the concrete visitors.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] When an operation is to be performed which is implemented using the Visitor pattern, it calls the `accept` method of the top-level element(s).
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] When the `accept` method is called in the program, its implementation is chosen based on both the dynamic type of the element and the static type of the visitor.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] When the associated `visit` method is called, its implementation is chosen based on both the dynamic type of the visitor and the static type of the element, as known from within the implementation of the `accept` method, which is the same as the dynamic type of the element.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] Thus, the implementation of the `visit` method is chosen based on both the dynamic type of the element and the dynamic type of the visitor.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] This effectively implements double dispatch.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] For languages whose object systems support multiple dispatch, not only single dispatch, such as Common Lisp or C# via the Dynamic Language Runtime (DLR), implementation of the visitor pattern is greatly simplified (a.k.a.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] Dynamic Visitor) by allowing use of simple function overloading to cover all the cases being visited.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] A dynamic visitor, provided it operates on public data only, conforms to the open/closed principle (since it does not modify extant structures) and to the single responsibility principle (since it implements the Visitor pattern in a separate component).
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] In this way, one algorithm can be written to traverse a graph of elements, and many different kinds of operations can be performed during that traversal by supplying different kinds of visitors to interact with the elements based on the dynamic types of both the elements and the visitors.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] This example declares a separate `ExpressionPrintingVisitor` class that takes care of the printing.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] If the introduction of a new concrete visitor is desired, a new class will be created to implement the Visitor interface, and new implementations for the Visit methods will be provided.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] The existing classes (Literal and Addition) will remain unchanged.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] In this case, it is the object's responsibility to know how to print itself on a stream.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] The visitor here is then the object, not the stream.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] Go does not support method overloading, so the visit methods need different names.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] The following example is in the language Java, and shows how the contents of a tree of nodes (in this case describing the components of a car) can be printed.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] Instead of creating `print` methods for each node subclass (`Wheel`, `Engine`, `Body`, and `Car`), one visitor class (`CarElementPrintVisitor`) performs the required printing action.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] Because different node subclasses require slightly different actions to print properly, `CarElementPrintVisitor` dispatches actions based on the class of the argument passed to its `visit` method.
[src:software-design/visitor-pattern] `CarElementDoVisitor`, which is analogous to a save operation for a different file format, does likewise.
